  42 def metric_variable(shape, dtype, validate_shape=True, name=None):
  43   """Create variable in `GraphKeys.(LOCAL|METRIC_VARIABLES)` collections.
  44 
  45   If running in a `DistributionStrategy` context, the variable will be
  46   "tower local". This means:
  47 
  48   *   The returned object will be a container with separate variables
  49       per replica/tower of the model.
  50 
  51   *   When writing to the variable, e.g. using `assign_add` in a metric
  52       update, the update will be applied to the variable local to the
  53       replica/tower.
  54 
  55   *   To get a metric's result value, we need to sum the variable values
  56       across the replicas/towers before computing the final answer.
  57       Furthermore, the final answer should be computed once instead of
  58       in every replica/tower. Both of these are accomplished by
  59       running the computation of the final result value inside
  60       `tf.contrib.distribution_strategy_context.get_tower_context(
  61       ).merge_call(fn)`.
  62       Inside the `merge_call()`, ops are only added to the graph once
  63       and access to a tower-local variable in a computation returns
  64       the sum across all replicas/towers.
  65 
  66   Args:
  67     shape: Shape of the created variable.
  68     dtype: Type of the created variable.
  69     validate_shape: (Optional) Whether shape validation is enabled for
  70       the created variable.
  71     name: (Optional) String name of the created variable.
  72 
  73   Returns:
  74     A (non-trainable) variable initialized to zero, or if inside a
  75     `DistributionStrategy` scope a tower-local variable container.
  76   """
  77   # Note that synchronization "ON_READ" implies trainable=False.
  78   return variable_scope.variable(
  79       lambda: array_ops.zeros(shape, dtype),
  80       collections=[
  81           ops.GraphKeys.LOCAL_VARIABLES, ops.GraphKeys.METRIC_VARIABLES
  82       ],
  83       validate_shape=validate_shape,
  84       synchronization=variable_scope.VariableSynchronization.ON_READ,
  85       aggregation=variable_scope.VariableAggregation.SUM,
  86       name=name)
  87

  89 def _remove_squeezable_dimensions(predictions, labels, weights):
  90   """Squeeze or expand last dim if needed.
  91 
  92   Squeezes last dim of `predictions` or `labels` if their rank differs by 1
  93   (using confusion_matrix.remove_squeezable_dimensions).
  94   Squeezes or expands last dim of `weights` if its rank differs by 1 from the
  95   new rank of `predictions`.
  96 
  97   If `weights` is scalar, it is kept scalar.
  98 
  99   This will use static shape if available. Otherwise, it will add graph
 100   operations, which could result in a performance hit.
 101 
 102   Args:
 103     predictions: Predicted values, a `Tensor` of arbitrary dimensions.
 104     labels: Optional label `Tensor` whose dimensions match `predictions`.
 105     weights: Optional weight scalar or `Tensor` whose dimensions match
 106       `predictions`.
 107 
 108   Returns:
 109     Tuple of `predictions`, `labels` and `weights`. Each of them possibly has
 110     the last dimension squeezed, `weights` could be extended by one dimension.
 111   """
 112   predictions = ops.convert_to_tensor(predictions)
 113   if labels is not None:
 114     labels, predictions = confusion_matrix.remove_squeezable_dimensions(
 115         labels, predictions)
 116     predictions.get_shape().assert_is_compatible_with(labels.get_shape())
 117 
 118   if weights is None:
 119     return predictions, labels, None
 120 
 121   weights = ops.convert_to_tensor(weights)
 122   weights_shape = weights.get_shape()
 123   weights_rank = weights_shape.ndims
 124   if weights_rank == 0:
 125     return predictions, labels, weights
 126 
 127   predictions_shape = predictions.get_shape()
 128   predictions_rank = predictions_shape.ndims
 129   if (predictions_rank is not None) and (weights_rank is not None):
 130     # Use static rank.
 131     if weights_rank - predictions_rank == 1:
 132       weights = array_ops.squeeze(weights, [-1])
 133     elif predictions_rank - weights_rank == 1:
 134       weights = array_ops.expand_dims(weights, [-1])
 135   else:
 136     # Use dynamic rank.
 137     weights_rank_tensor = array_ops.rank(weights)
 138     rank_diff = weights_rank_tensor - array_ops.rank(predictions)
 139 
 140     def _maybe_expand_weights():
 141       return control_flow_ops.cond(
 142           math_ops.equal(rank_diff, -1),
 143           lambda: array_ops.expand_dims(weights, [-1]), lambda: weights)
 144 
 145     # Don't attempt squeeze if it will fail based on static check.
 146     if ((weights_rank is not None) and
 147         (not weights_shape.dims[-1].is_compatible_with(1))):
 148       maybe_squeeze_weights = lambda: weights
 149     else:
 150       maybe_squeeze_weights = lambda: array_ops.squeeze(weights, [-1])
 151 
 152     def _maybe_adjust_weights():
 153       return control_flow_ops.cond(
 154           math_ops.equal(rank_diff, 1), maybe_squeeze_weights,
 155           _maybe_expand_weights)
 156 
 157     # If weights are scalar, do nothing. Otherwise, try to add or remove a
 158     # dimension to match predictions.
 159     weights = control_flow_ops.cond(
 160         math_ops.equal(weights_rank_tensor, 0), lambda: weights,
 161         _maybe_adjust_weights)
 162   return predictions, labels, weights
 163

 165 def _maybe_expand_labels(labels, predictions):
 166   """If necessary, expand `labels` along last dimension to match `predictions`.
 167 
 168   Args:
 169     labels: `Tensor` or `SparseTensor` with shape
 170       [D1, ... DN, num_labels] or [D1, ... DN]. The latter implies
 171       num_labels=1, in which case the result is an expanded `labels` with shape
 172       [D1, ... DN, 1].
 173     predictions: `Tensor` with shape [D1, ... DN, num_classes].
 174 
 175   Returns:
 176     `labels` with the same rank as `predictions`.
 177 
 178   Raises:
 179     ValueError: if `labels` has invalid shape.
 180   """
 181   with ops.name_scope(None, 'expand_labels', (labels, predictions)) as scope:
 182     labels = sparse_tensor.convert_to_tensor_or_sparse_tensor(labels)
 183 
 184     # If sparse, expand sparse shape.
 185     if isinstance(labels, sparse_tensor.SparseTensor):
 186       return control_flow_ops.cond(
 187           math_ops.equal(
 188               array_ops.rank(predictions),
 189               array_ops.size(labels.dense_shape) + 1),
 190           lambda: sparse_ops.sparse_reshape(  # pylint: disable=g-long-lambda
 191               labels,
 192               shape=array_ops.concat((labels.dense_shape, (1,)), 0),
 193               name=scope),
 194           lambda: labels)
 195 
 196     # Otherwise, try to use static shape.
 197     labels_rank = labels.get_shape().ndims
 198     if labels_rank is not None:
 199       predictions_rank = predictions.get_shape().ndims
 200       if predictions_rank is not None:
 201         if predictions_rank == labels_rank:
 202           return labels
 203         if predictions_rank == labels_rank + 1:
 204           return array_ops.expand_dims(labels, -1, name=scope)
 205         raise ValueError(
 206             'Unexpected labels shape %s for predictions shape %s.' %
 207             (labels.get_shape(), predictions.get_shape()))
 208 
 209     # Otherwise, use dynamic shape.
 210     return control_flow_ops.cond(
 211         math_ops.equal(array_ops.rank(predictions),
 212                        array_ops.rank(labels) + 1),
 213         lambda: array_ops.expand_dims(labels, -1, name=scope), lambda: labels)
 214

 216 def _safe_div(numerator, denominator, name):
 217   """Divides two tensors element-wise, returning 0 if the denominator is <= 0.
 218 
 219   Args:
 220     numerator: A real `Tensor`.
 221     denominator: A real `Tensor`, with dtype matching `numerator`.
 222     name: Name for the returned op.
 223 
 224   Returns:
 225     0 if `denominator` <= 0, else `numerator` / `denominator`
 226   """
 227   t = math_ops.truediv(numerator, denominator)
 228   zero = array_ops.zeros_like(t, dtype=denominator.dtype)
 229   condition = math_ops.greater(denominator, zero)
 230   zero = math_ops.cast(zero, t.dtype)
 231   return array_ops.where(condition, t, zero, name=name)
 232 
 233 
 234 def _safe_scalar_div(numerator, denominator, name):
 235   """Divides two values, returning 0 if the denominator is 0.
 236 
 237   Args:
 238     numerator: A scalar `float64` `Tensor`.
 239     denominator: A scalar `float64` `Tensor`.
 240     name: Name for the returned op.
 241 
 242   Returns:
 243     0 if `denominator` == 0, else `numerator` / `denominator`
 244   """
 245   numerator.get_shape().with_rank_at_most(1)
 246   denominator.get_shape().with_rank_at_most(1)
 247   return control_flow_ops.cond(
 248       math_ops.equal(
 249           array_ops.constant(0.0, dtype=dtypes.float64), denominator),
 250       lambda: array_ops.constant(0.0, dtype=dtypes.float64),
 251       lambda: math_ops.div(numerator, denominator),
 252       name=name)

 255 def _streaming_confusion_matrix(labels, predictions, num_classes, weights=None):
 256   """Calculate a streaming confusion matrix.
 257 
 258   Calculates a confusion matrix. For estimation over a stream of data,
 259   the function creates an  `update_op` operation.
 260 
 261   Args:
 262     labels: A `Tensor` of ground truth labels with shape [batch size] and of
 263       type `int32` or `int64`. The tensor will be flattened if its rank > 1.
 264     predictions: A `Tensor` of prediction results for semantic labels, whose
 265       shape is [batch size] and type `int32` or `int64`. The tensor will be
 266       flattened if its rank > 1.
 267     num_classes: The possible number of labels the prediction task can
 268       have. This value must be provided, since a confusion matrix of
 269       dimension = [num_classes, num_classes] will be allocated.
 270     weights: Optional `Tensor` whose rank is either 0, or the same rank as
 271       `labels`, and must be broadcastable to `labels` (i.e., all dimensions must
 272       be either `1`, or the same as the corresponding `labels` dimension).
 273 
 274   Returns:
 275     total_cm: A `Tensor` representing the confusion matrix.
 276     update_op: An operation that increments the confusion matrix.
 277   """
 278   # Local variable to accumulate the predictions in the confusion matrix.
 279   total_cm = metric_variable(
 280       [num_classes, num_classes], dtypes.float64, name='total_confusion_matrix')
 281 
 282   # Cast the type to int64 required by confusion_matrix_ops.
 283   predictions = math_ops.to_int64(predictions)
 284   labels = math_ops.to_int64(labels)
 285   num_classes = math_ops.to_int64(num_classes)
 286 
 287   # Flatten the input if its rank > 1.
 288   if predictions.get_shape().ndims > 1:
 289     predictions = array_ops.reshape(predictions, [-1])
 290 
 291   if labels.get_shape().ndims > 1:
 292     labels = array_ops.reshape(labels, [-1])
 293 
 294   if (weights is not None) and (weights.get_shape().ndims > 1):
 295     weights = array_ops.reshape(weights, [-1])
 296 
 297   # Accumulate the prediction to current confusion matrix.
 298   current_cm = confusion_matrix.confusion_matrix(
 299       labels, predictions, num_classes, weights=weights, dtype=dtypes.float64)
 300   update_op = state_ops.assign_add(total_cm, current_cm)
 301   return total_cm, update_op
 302

 304 def _aggregate_across_towers(metrics_collections, metric_value_fn, *args):
 305   """Aggregate metric value across towers."""
 306   def fn(distribution, *a):
 307     """Call `metric_value_fn` in the correct control flow context."""
 308     if hasattr(distribution, '_outer_control_flow_context'):
 309       # If there was an outer context captured before this method was called,
 310       # then we enter that context to create the metric value op. If the
 311       # caputred context is `None`, ops.control_dependencies(None) gives the
 312       # desired behavior. Else we use `Enter` and `Exit` to enter and exit the
 313       # captured context.
 314       # This special handling is needed because sometimes the metric is created
 315       # inside a while_loop (and perhaps a TPU rewrite context). But we don't
 316       # want the value op to be evaluated every step or on the TPU. So we
 317       # create it outside so that it can be evaluated at the end on the host,
 318       # once the update ops have been evaluted.
 319 
 320       # pylint: disable=protected-access
 321       if distribution._outer_control_flow_context is None:
 322         with ops.control_dependencies(None):
 323           metric_value = metric_value_fn(distribution, *a)
 324       else:
 325         distribution._outer_control_flow_context.Enter()
 326         metric_value = metric_value_fn(distribution, *a)
 327         distribution._outer_control_flow_context.Exit()
 328         # pylint: enable=protected-access
 329     else:
 330       metric_value = metric_value_fn(distribution, *a)
 331     if metrics_collections:
 332       ops.add_to_collections(metrics_collections, metric_value)
 333     return metric_value
 334 
 335   return distribution_strategy_context.get_tower_context().merge_call(fn, *args)

 338 @tf_export('metrics.mean')
 339 def mean(values,
 340          weights=None,
 341          metrics_collections=None,
 342          updates_collections=None,
 343          name=None):
 344   """Computes the (weighted) mean of the given values.
 345 
 346   The `mean` function creates two local variables, `total` and `count`
 347   that are used to compute the average of `values`. This average is ultimately
 348   returned as `mean` which is an idempotent operation that simply divides
 349   `total` by `count`.
 350 
 351   For estimation of the metric over a stream of data, the function creates an
 352   `update_op` operation that updates these variables and returns the `mean`.
 353   `update_op` increments `total` with the reduced sum of the product of `values`
 354   and `weights`, and it increments `count` with the reduced sum of `weights`.
 355 
 356   If `weights` is `None`, weights default to 1. Use weights of 0 to mask values.
 357 
 358   Args:
 359     values: A `Tensor` of arbitrary dimensions.
 360     weights: Optional `Tensor` whose rank is either 0, or the same rank as
 361       `values`, and must be broadcastable to `values` (i.e., all dimensions must
 362       be either `1`, or the same as the corresponding `values` dimension).
 363     metrics_collections: An optional list of collections that `mean`
 364       should be added to.
 365     updates_collections: An optional list of collections that `update_op`
 366       should be added to.
 367     name: An optional variable_scope name.
 368 
 369   Returns:
 370     mean: A `Tensor` representing the current mean, the value of `total` divided
 371       by `count`.
 372     update_op: An operation that increments the `total` and `count` variables
 373       appropriately and whose value matches `mean_value`.
 374 
 375   Raises:
 376     ValueError: If `weights` is not `None` and its shape doesn't match `values`,
 377       or if either `metrics_collections` or `updates_collections` are not a list
 378       or tuple.
 379     RuntimeError: If eager execution is enabled.
 380   """
 381   if context.executing_eagerly():
 382     raise RuntimeError('tf.metrics.mean is not supported when eager execution '
 383                        'is enabled.')
 384 
 385   with variable_scope.variable_scope(name, 'mean', (values, weights)):
 386     values = math_ops.to_float(values)
 387 
 388     total = metric_variable([], dtypes.float32, name='total')
 389     count = metric_variable([], dtypes.float32, name='count')
 390 
 391     if weights is None:
 392       num_values = math_ops.to_float(array_ops.size(values))
 393     else:
 394       values, _, weights = _remove_squeezable_dimensions(
 395           predictions=values, labels=None, weights=weights)
 396       weights = weights_broadcast_ops.broadcast_weights(
 397           math_ops.to_float(weights), values)
 398       values = math_ops.multiply(values, weights)
 399       num_values = math_ops.reduce_sum(weights)
 400 
 401     update_total_op = state_ops.assign_add(total, math_ops.reduce_sum(values))
 402     with ops.control_dependencies([values]):
 403       update_count_op = state_ops.assign_add(count, num_values)
 404 
 405     compute_mean = lambda _, t, c: _safe_div(t, c, 'value')
 406 
 407     mean_t = _aggregate_across_towers(
 408         metrics_collections, compute_mean, total, count)
 409     update_op = _safe_div(update_total_op, update_count_op, 'update_op')
 410 
 411     if updates_collections:
 412       ops.add_to_collections(updates_collections, update_op)
 413 
 414     return mean_t, update_op
 415

 417 @tf_export('metrics.accuracy')
 418 def accuracy(labels,
 419              predictions,
 420              weights=None,
 421              metrics_collections=None,
 422              updates_collections=None,
 423              name=None):
 424   """Calculates how often `predictions` matches `labels`.
 425 
 426   The `accuracy` function creates two local variables, `total` and
 427   `count` that are used to compute the frequency with which `predictions`
 428   matches `labels`. This frequency is ultimately returned as `accuracy`: an
 429   idempotent operation that simply divides `total` by `count`.
 430 
 431   For estimation of the metric over a stream of data, the function creates an
 432   `update_op` operation that updates these variables and returns the `accuracy`.
 433   Internally, an `is_correct` operation computes a `Tensor` with elements 1.0
 434   where the corresponding elements of `predictions` and `labels` match and 0.0
 435   otherwise. Then `update_op` increments `total` with the reduced sum of the
 436   product of `weights` and `is_correct`, and it increments `count` with the
 437   reduced sum of `weights`.
 438 
 439   If `weights` is `None`, weights default to 1. Use weights of 0 to mask values.
 440 
 441   Args:
 442     labels: The ground truth values, a `Tensor` whose shape matches
 443       `predictions`.
 444     predictions: The predicted values, a `Tensor` of any shape.
 445     weights: Optional `Tensor` whose rank is either 0, or the same rank as
 446       `labels`, and must be broadcastable to `labels` (i.e., all dimensions must
 447       be either `1`, or the same as the corresponding `labels` dimension).
 448     metrics_collections: An optional list of collections that `accuracy` should
 449       be added to.
 450     updates_collections: An optional list of collections that `update_op` should
 451       be added to.
 452     name: An optional variable_scope name.
 453 
 454   Returns:
 455     accuracy: A `Tensor` representing the accuracy, the value of `total` divided
 456       by `count`.
 457     update_op: An operation that increments the `total` and `count` variables
 458       appropriately and whose value matches `accuracy`.
 459 
 460   Raises:
 461     ValueError: If `predictions` and `labels` have mismatched shapes, or if
 462       `weights` is not `None` and its shape doesn't match `predictions`, or if
 463       either `metrics_collections` or `updates_collections` are not a list or
 464       tuple.
 465     RuntimeError: If eager execution is enabled.
 466   """
 467   if context.executing_eagerly():
 468     raise RuntimeError('tf.metrics.accuracy is not supported when eager '
 469                        'execution is enabled.')
 470 
 471   predictions, labels, weights = _remove_squeezable_dimensions(
 472       predictions=predictions, labels=labels, weights=weights)
 473   predictions.get_shape().assert_is_compatible_with(labels.get_shape())
 474   if labels.dtype != predictions.dtype:
 475     predictions = math_ops.cast(predictions, labels.dtype)
 476   is_correct = math_ops.to_float(math_ops.equal(predictions, labels))
 477   return mean(is_correct, weights, metrics_collections, updates_collections,
 478               name or 'accuracy')

 481 def _confusion_matrix_at_thresholds(labels,
 482                                     predictions,
 483                                     thresholds,
 484                                     weights=None,
 485                                     includes=None):
 486   """Computes true_positives, false_negatives, true_negatives, false_positives.
 487 
 488   This function creates up to four local variables, `true_positives`,
 489   `true_negatives`, `false_positives` and `false_negatives`.
 490   `true_positive[i]` is defined as the total weight of values in `predictions`
 491   above `thresholds[i]` whose corresponding entry in `labels` is `True`.
 492   `false_negatives[i]` is defined as the total weight of values in `predictions`
 493   at most `thresholds[i]` whose corresponding entry in `labels` is `True`.
 494   `true_negatives[i]` is defined as the total weight of values in `predictions`
 495   at most `thresholds[i]` whose corresponding entry in `labels` is `False`.
 496   `false_positives[i]` is defined as the total weight of values in `predictions`
 497   above `thresholds[i]` whose corresponding entry in `labels` is `False`.
 498 
 499   For estimation of these metrics over a stream of data, for each metric the
 500   function respectively creates an `update_op` operation that updates the
 501   variable and returns its value.
 502 
 503   If `weights` is `None`, weights default to 1. Use weights of 0 to mask values.
 504 
 505   Args:
 506     labels: A `Tensor` whose shape matches `predictions`. Will be cast to
 507       `bool`.
 508     predictions: A floating point `Tensor` of arbitrary shape and whose values
 509       are in the range `[0, 1]`.
 510     thresholds: A python list or tuple of float thresholds in `[0, 1]`.
 511     weights: Optional `Tensor` whose rank is either 0, or the same rank as
 512       `labels`, and must be broadcastable to `labels` (i.e., all dimensions must
 513       be either `1`, or the same as the corresponding `labels` dimension).
 514     includes: Tuple of keys to return, from 'tp', 'fn', 'tn', fp'. If `None`,
 515         default to all four.
 516 
 517   Returns:
 518     values: Dict of variables of shape `[len(thresholds)]`. Keys are from
 519         `includes`.
 520     update_ops: Dict of operations that increments the `values`. Keys are from
 521         `includes`.
 522 
 523   Raises:
 524     ValueError: If `predictions` and `labels` have mismatched shapes, or if
 525       `weights` is not `None` and its shape doesn't match `predictions`, or if
 526       `includes` contains invalid keys.
 527   """
 528   all_includes = ('tp', 'fn', 'tn', 'fp')
 529   if includes is None:
 530     includes = all_includes
 531   else:
 532     for include in includes:
 533       if include not in all_includes:
 534         raise ValueError('Invalid key: %s.' % include)
 535 
 536   with ops.control_dependencies([
 537       check_ops.assert_greater_equal(
 538           predictions,
 539           math_ops.cast(0.0, dtype=predictions.dtype),
 540           message='predictions must be in [0, 1]'),
 541       check_ops.assert_less_equal(
 542           predictions,
 543           math_ops.cast(1.0, dtype=predictions.dtype),
 544           message='predictions must be in [0, 1]')
 545   ]):
 546     predictions, labels, weights = _remove_squeezable_dimensions(
 547         predictions=math_ops.to_float(predictions),
 548         labels=math_ops.cast(labels, dtype=dtypes.bool),
 549         weights=weights)
 550 
 551   num_thresholds = len(thresholds)
 552 
 553   # Reshape predictions and labels.
 554   predictions_2d = array_ops.reshape(predictions, [-1, 1])
 555   labels_2d = array_ops.reshape(
 556       math_ops.cast(labels, dtype=dtypes.bool), [1, -1])
 557 
 558   # Use static shape if known.
 559   num_predictions = predictions_2d.get_shape().as_list()[0]
 560 
 561   # Otherwise use dynamic shape.
 562   if num_predictions is None:
 563     num_predictions = array_ops.shape(predictions_2d)[0]
 564   thresh_tiled = array_ops.tile(
 565       array_ops.expand_dims(array_ops.constant(thresholds), [1]),
 566       array_ops.stack([1, num_predictions]))
 567 
 568   # Tile the predictions after thresholding them across different thresholds.
 569   pred_is_pos = math_ops.greater(
 570       array_ops.tile(array_ops.transpose(predictions_2d), [num_thresholds, 1]),
 571       thresh_tiled)
 572   if ('fn' in includes) or ('tn' in includes):
 573     pred_is_neg = math_ops.logical_not(pred_is_pos)
 574 
 575   # Tile labels by number of thresholds
 576   label_is_pos = array_ops.tile(labels_2d, [num_thresholds, 1])
 577   if ('fp' in includes) or ('tn' in includes):
 578     label_is_neg = math_ops.logical_not(label_is_pos)
 579 
 580   if weights is not None:
 581     weights = weights_broadcast_ops.broadcast_weights(
 582         math_ops.to_float(weights), predictions)
 583     weights_tiled = array_ops.tile(
 584         array_ops.reshape(weights, [1, -1]), [num_thresholds, 1])
 585     thresh_tiled.get_shape().assert_is_compatible_with(
 586         weights_tiled.get_shape())
 587   else:
 588     weights_tiled = None
 589 
 590   values = {}
 591   update_ops = {}
 592 
 593   if 'tp' in includes:
 594     true_p = metric_variable(
 595         [num_thresholds], dtypes.float32, name='true_positives')
 596     is_true_positive = math_ops.to_float(
 597         math_ops.logical_and(label_is_pos, pred_is_pos))
 598     if weights_tiled is not None:
 599       is_true_positive *= weights_tiled
 600     update_ops['tp'] = state_ops.assign_add(true_p,
 601                                             math_ops.reduce_sum(
 602                                                 is_true_positive, 1))
 603     values['tp'] = true_p
 604 
 605   if 'fn' in includes:
 606     false_n = metric_variable(
 607         [num_thresholds], dtypes.float32, name='false_negatives')
 608     is_false_negative = math_ops.to_float(
 609         math_ops.logical_and(label_is_pos, pred_is_neg))
 610     if weights_tiled is not None:
 611       is_false_negative *= weights_tiled
 612     update_ops['fn'] = state_ops.assign_add(false_n,
 613                                             math_ops.reduce_sum(
 614                                                 is_false_negative, 1))
 615     values['fn'] = false_n
 616 
 617   if 'tn' in includes:
 618     true_n = metric_variable(
 619         [num_thresholds], dtypes.float32, name='true_negatives')
 620     is_true_negative = math_ops.to_float(
 621         math_ops.logical_and(label_is_neg, pred_is_neg))
 622     if weights_tiled is not None:
 623       is_true_negative *= weights_tiled
 624     update_ops['tn'] = state_ops.assign_add(true_n,
 625                                             math_ops.reduce_sum(
 626                                                 is_true_negative, 1))
 627     values['tn'] = true_n
 628 
 629   if 'fp' in includes:
 630     false_p = metric_variable(
 631         [num_thresholds], dtypes.float32, name='false_positives')
 632     is_false_positive = math_ops.to_float(
 633         math_ops.logical_and(label_is_neg, pred_is_pos))
 634     if weights_tiled is not None:
 635       is_false_positive *= weights_tiled
 636     update_ops['fp'] = state_ops.assign_add(false_p,
 637                                             math_ops.reduce_sum(
 638                                                 is_false_positive, 1))
 639     values['fp'] = false_p
 640 
 641   return values, update_ops
 642 
 643 
 644 def _aggregate_variable(v, collections):
 645   f = lambda distribution, value: distribution.read_var(value)
 646   return _aggregate_across_towers(collections, f, v)

 649 @tf_export('metrics.auc')
 650 def auc(labels,
 651         predictions,
 652         weights=None,
 653         num_thresholds=200,
 654         metrics_collections=None,
 655         updates_collections=None,
 656         curve='ROC',
 657         name=None,
 658         summation_method='trapezoidal'):
 659   """Computes the approximate AUC via a Riemann sum.
 660 
 661   The `auc` function creates four local variables, `true_positives`,
 662   `true_negatives`, `false_positives` and `false_negatives` that are used to
 663   compute the AUC. To discretize the AUC curve, a linearly spaced set of
 664   thresholds is used to compute pairs of recall and precision values. The area
 665   under the ROC-curve is therefore computed using the height of the recall
 666   values by the false positive rate, while the area under the PR-curve is the
 667   computed using the height of the precision values by the recall.
 668 
 669   This value is ultimately returned as `auc`, an idempotent operation that
 670   computes the area under a discretized curve of precision versus recall values
 671   (computed using the aforementioned variables). The `num_thresholds` variable
 672   controls the degree of discretization with larger numbers of thresholds more
 673   closely approximating the true AUC. The quality of the approximation may vary
 674   dramatically depending on `num_thresholds`.
 675 
 676   For best results, `predictions` should be distributed approximately uniformly
 677   in the range [0, 1] and not peaked around 0 or 1. The quality of the AUC
 678   approximation may be poor if this is not the case. Setting `summation_method`
 679   to 'minoring' or 'majoring' can help quantify the error in the approximation
 680   by providing lower or upper bound estimate of the AUC.
 681 
 682   For estimation of the metric over a stream of data, the function creates an
 683   `update_op` operation that updates these variables and returns the `auc`.
 684 
 685   If `weights` is `None`, weights default to 1. Use weights of 0 to mask values.
 686 
 687   Args:
 688     labels: A `Tensor` whose shape matches `predictions`. Will be cast to
 689       `bool`.
 690     predictions: A floating point `Tensor` of arbitrary shape and whose values
 691       are in the range `[0, 1]`.
 692     weights: Optional `Tensor` whose rank is either 0, or the same rank as
 693       `labels`, and must be broadcastable to `labels` (i.e., all dimensions must
 694       be either `1`, or the same as the corresponding `labels` dimension).
 695     num_thresholds: The number of thresholds to use when discretizing the roc
 696       curve.
 697     metrics_collections: An optional list of collections that `auc` should be
 698       added to.
 699     updates_collections: An optional list of collections that `update_op` should
 700       be added to.
 701     curve: Specifies the name of the curve to be computed, 'ROC' [default] or
 702       'PR' for the Precision-Recall-curve.
 703     name: An optional variable_scope name.
 704     summation_method: Specifies the Riemann summation method used
 705       (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Riemann_sum): 'trapezoidal' [default] that
 706       applies the trapezoidal rule; 'careful_interpolation', a variant of it
 707       differing only by a more correct interpolation scheme for PR-AUC -
 708       interpolating (true/false) positives but not the ratio that is precision;
 709       'minoring' that applies left summation for increasing intervals and right
 710       summation for decreasing intervals; 'majoring' that does the opposite.
 711       Note that 'careful_interpolation' is strictly preferred to 'trapezoidal'
 712       (to be deprecated soon) as it applies the same method for ROC, and a
 713       better one (see Davis & Goadrich 2006 for details) for the PR curve.
 714 
 715   Returns:
 716     auc: A scalar `Tensor` representing the current area-under-curve.
 717     update_op: An operation that increments the `true_positives`,
 718       `true_negatives`, `false_positives` and `false_negatives` variables
 719       appropriately and whose value matches `auc`.
 720 
 721   Raises:
 722     ValueError: If `predictions` and `labels` have mismatched shapes, or if
 723       `weights` is not `None` and its shape doesn't match `predictions`, or if
 724       either `metrics_collections` or `updates_collections` are not a list or
 725       tuple.
 726     RuntimeError: If eager execution is enabled.
 727   """
 728   if context.executing_eagerly():
 729     raise RuntimeError('tf.metrics.auc is not supported when eager execution '
 730                        'is enabled.')
 731 
 732   with variable_scope.variable_scope(name, 'auc',
 733                                      (labels, predictions, weights)):
 734     if curve != 'ROC' and curve != 'PR':
 735       raise ValueError('curve must be either ROC or PR, %s unknown' % (curve))
 736     kepsilon = 1e-7  # to account for floating point imprecisions
 737     thresholds = [
 738         (i + 1) * 1.0 / (num_thresholds - 1) for i in range(num_thresholds - 2)
 739     ]
 740     thresholds = [0.0 - kepsilon] + thresholds + [1.0 + kepsilon]
 741 
 742     values, update_ops = _confusion_matrix_at_thresholds(
 743         labels, predictions, thresholds, weights)
 744 
 745     # Add epsilons to avoid dividing by 0.
 746     epsilon = 1.0e-6
 747 
 748     def interpolate_pr_auc(tp, fp, fn):
 749       """Interpolation formula inspired by section 4 of Davis & Goadrich 2006.
 750 
 751       Note here we derive & use a closed formula not present in the paper
 752       - as follows:
 753       Modeling all of TP (true positive weight),
 754       FP (false positive weight) and their sum P = TP + FP (positive weight)
 755       as varying linearly within each interval [A, B] between successive
 756       thresholds, we get
 757         Precision = (TP_A + slope * (P - P_A)) / P
 758       with slope = dTP / dP = (TP_B - TP_A) / (P_B - P_A).
 759       The area within the interval is thus (slope / total_pos_weight) times
 760         int_A^B{Precision.dP} = int_A^B{(TP_A + slope * (P - P_A)) * dP / P}
 761         int_A^B{Precision.dP} = int_A^B{slope * dP + intercept * dP / P}
 762       where intercept = TP_A - slope * P_A = TP_B - slope * P_B, resulting in
 763         int_A^B{Precision.dP} = TP_B - TP_A + intercept * log(P_B / P_A)
 764       Bringing back the factor (slope / total_pos_weight) we'd put aside, we get
 765          slope * [dTP + intercept *  log(P_B / P_A)] / total_pos_weight
 766       where dTP == TP_B - TP_A.
 767       Note that when P_A == 0 the above calculation simplifies into
 768         int_A^B{Precision.dTP} = int_A^B{slope * dTP} = slope * (TP_B - TP_A)
 769       which is really equivalent to imputing constant precision throughout the
 770       first bucket having >0 true positives.
 771 
 772       Args:
 773         tp: true positive counts
 774         fp: false positive counts
 775         fn: false negative counts
 776       Returns:
 777         pr_auc: an approximation of the area under the P-R curve.
 778       """
 779       dtp = tp[:num_thresholds - 1] - tp[1:]
 780       p = tp + fp
 781       prec_slope = _safe_div(dtp, p[:num_thresholds - 1] - p[1:], 'prec_slope')
 782       intercept = tp[1:] - math_ops.multiply(prec_slope, p[1:])
 783       safe_p_ratio = array_ops.where(
 784           math_ops.logical_and(p[:num_thresholds - 1] > 0, p[1:] > 0),
 785           _safe_div(p[:num_thresholds - 1], p[1:], 'recall_relative_ratio'),
 786           array_ops.ones_like(p[1:]))
 787       return math_ops.reduce_sum(
 788           _safe_div(
 789               prec_slope * (dtp + intercept * math_ops.log(safe_p_ratio)),
 790               tp[1:] + fn[1:],
 791               name='pr_auc_increment'),
 792           name='interpolate_pr_auc')
 793 
 794     def compute_auc(tp, fn, tn, fp, name):
 795       """Computes the roc-auc or pr-auc based on confusion counts."""
 796       if curve == 'PR':
 797         if summation_method == 'trapezoidal':
 798           logging.warning(
 799               'Trapezoidal rule is known to produce incorrect PR-AUCs; '
 800               'please switch to "careful_interpolation" instead.')
 801         elif summation_method == 'careful_interpolation':
 802           # This one is a bit tricky and is handled separately.
 803           return interpolate_pr_auc(tp, fp, fn)
 804       rec = math_ops.div(tp + epsilon, tp + fn + epsilon)
 805       if curve == 'ROC':
 806         fp_rate = math_ops.div(fp, fp + tn + epsilon)
 807         x = fp_rate
 808         y = rec
 809       else:  # curve == 'PR'.
 810         prec = math_ops.div(tp + epsilon, tp + fp + epsilon)
 811         x = rec
 812         y = prec
 813       if summation_method in ('trapezoidal', 'careful_interpolation'):
 814         # Note that the case ('PR', 'careful_interpolation') has been handled
 815         # above.
 816         return math_ops.reduce_sum(
 817             math_ops.multiply(x[:num_thresholds - 1] - x[1:],
 818                               (y[:num_thresholds - 1] + y[1:]) / 2.),
 819             name=name)
 820       elif summation_method == 'minoring':
 821         return math_ops.reduce_sum(
 822             math_ops.multiply(x[:num_thresholds - 1] - x[1:],
 823                               math_ops.minimum(y[:num_thresholds - 1], y[1:])),
 824             name=name)
 825       elif summation_method == 'majoring':
 826         return math_ops.reduce_sum(
 827             math_ops.multiply(x[:num_thresholds - 1] - x[1:],
 828                               math_ops.maximum(y[:num_thresholds - 1], y[1:])),
 829             name=name)
 830       else:
 831         raise ValueError('Invalid summation_method: %s' % summation_method)
 832 
 833     # sum up the areas of all the trapeziums
 834     def compute_auc_value(_, values):
 835       return compute_auc(values['tp'], values['fn'], values['tn'], values['fp'],
 836                          'value')
 837 
 838     auc_value = _aggregate_across_towers(
 839         metrics_collections, compute_auc_value, values)
 840     update_op = compute_auc(update_ops['tp'], update_ops['fn'],
 841                             update_ops['tn'], update_ops['fp'], 'update_op')
 842 
 843     if updates_collections:
 844       ops.add_to_collections(updates_collections, update_op)
 845 
 846     return auc_value, update_op
 847

 849 @tf_export('metrics.mean_absolute_error')
 850 def mean_absolute_error(labels,
 851                         predictions,
 852                         weights=None,
 853                         metrics_collections=None,
 854                         updates_collections=None,
 855                         name=None):
 856   """Computes the mean absolute error between the labels and predictions.
 857 
 858   The `mean_absolute_error` function creates two local variables,
 859   `total` and `count` that are used to compute the mean absolute error. This
 860   average is weighted by `weights`, and it is ultimately returned as
 861   `mean_absolute_error`: an idempotent operation that simply divides `total` by
 862   `count`.
 863 
 864   For estimation of the metric over a stream of data, the function creates an
 865   `update_op` operation that updates these variables and returns the
 866   `mean_absolute_error`. Internally, an `absolute_errors` operation computes the
 867   absolute value of the differences between `predictions` and `labels`. Then
 868   `update_op` increments `total` with the reduced sum of the product of
 869   `weights` and `absolute_errors`, and it increments `count` with the reduced
 870   sum of `weights`
 871 
 872   If `weights` is `None`, weights default to 1. Use weights of 0 to mask values.
 873 
 874   Args:
 875     labels: A `Tensor` of the same shape as `predictions`.
 876     predictions: A `Tensor` of arbitrary shape.
 877     weights: Optional `Tensor` whose rank is either 0, or the same rank as
 878       `labels`, and must be broadcastable to `labels` (i.e., all dimensions must
 879       be either `1`, or the same as the corresponding `labels` dimension).
 880     metrics_collections: An optional list of collections that
 881       `mean_absolute_error` should be added to.
 882     updates_collections: An optional list of collections that `update_op` should
 883       be added to.
 884     name: An optional variable_scope name.
 885 
 886   Returns:
 887     mean_absolute_error: A `Tensor` representing the current mean, the value of
 888       `total` divided by `count`.
 889     update_op: An operation that increments the `total` and `count` variables
 890       appropriately and whose value matches `mean_absolute_error`.
 891 
 892   Raises:
 893     ValueError: If `predictions` and `labels` have mismatched shapes, or if
 894       `weights` is not `None` and its shape doesn't match `predictions`, or if
 895       either `metrics_collections` or `updates_collections` are not a list or
 896       tuple.
 897     RuntimeError: If eager execution is enabled.
 898   """
 899   if context.executing_eagerly():
 900     raise RuntimeError('tf.metrics.mean_absolute_error is not supported '
 901                        'when eager execution is enabled.')
 902 
 903   predictions, labels, weights = _remove_squeezable_dimensions(
 904       predictions=predictions, labels=labels, weights=weights)
 905   absolute_errors = math_ops.abs(predictions - labels)
 906   return mean(absolute_errors, weights, metrics_collections,
 907               updates_collections, name or 'mean_absolute_error')

 910 @tf_export('metrics.mean_cosine_distance')
 911 def mean_cosine_distance(labels,
 912                          predictions,
 913                          dim,
 914                          weights=None,
 915                          metrics_collections=None,
 916                          updates_collections=None,
 917                          name=None):
 918   """Computes the cosine distance between the labels and predictions.
 919 
 920   The `mean_cosine_distance` function creates two local variables,
 921   `total` and `count` that are used to compute the average cosine distance
 922   between `predictions` and `labels`. This average is weighted by `weights`,
 923   and it is ultimately returned as `mean_distance`, which is an idempotent
 924   operation that simply divides `total` by `count`.
 925 
 926   For estimation of the metric over a stream of data, the function creates an
 927   `update_op` operation that updates these variables and returns the
 928   `mean_distance`.
 929 
 930   If `weights` is `None`, weights default to 1. Use weights of 0 to mask values.
 931 
 932   Args:
 933     labels: A `Tensor` of arbitrary shape.
 934     predictions: A `Tensor` of the same shape as `labels`.
 935     dim: The dimension along which the cosine distance is computed.
 936     weights: Optional `Tensor` whose rank is either 0, or the same rank as
 937       `labels`, and must be broadcastable to `labels` (i.e., all dimensions must
 938       be either `1`, or the same as the corresponding `labels` dimension). Also,
 939       dimension `dim` must be `1`.
 940     metrics_collections: An optional list of collections that the metric
 941       value variable should be added to.
 942     updates_collections: An optional list of collections that the metric update
 943       ops should be added to.
 944     name: An optional variable_scope name.
 945 
 946   Returns:
 947     mean_distance: A `Tensor` representing the current mean, the value of
 948       `total` divided by `count`.
 949     update_op: An operation that increments the `total` and `count` variables
 950       appropriately.
 951 
 952   Raises:
 953     ValueError: If `predictions` and `labels` have mismatched shapes, or if
 954       `weights` is not `None` and its shape doesn't match `predictions`, or if
 955       either `metrics_collections` or `updates_collections` are not a list or
 956       tuple.
 957     RuntimeError: If eager execution is enabled.
 958   """
 959   if context.executing_eagerly():
 960     raise RuntimeError('tf.metrics.mean_cosine_distance is not supported when '
 961                        'eager execution is enabled.')
 962 
 963   predictions, labels, weights = _remove_squeezable_dimensions(
 964       predictions=predictions, labels=labels, weights=weights)
 965   radial_diffs = math_ops.multiply(predictions, labels)
 966   radial_diffs = math_ops.reduce_sum(
 967       radial_diffs, reduction_indices=[
 968           dim,
 969       ], keepdims=True)
 970   mean_distance, update_op = mean(radial_diffs, weights, None, None, name or
 971                                   'mean_cosine_distance')
 972   mean_distance = math_ops.subtract(1.0, mean_distance)
 973   update_op = math_ops.subtract(1.0, update_op)
 974 
 975   if metrics_collections:
 976     ops.add_to_collections(metrics_collections, mean_distance)
 977 
 978   if updates_collections:
 979     ops.add_to_collections(updates_collections, update_op)
 980 
 981   return mean_distance, update_op

 984 @tf_export('metrics.mean_per_class_accuracy')
 985 def mean_per_class_accuracy(labels,
 986                             predictions,
 987                             num_classes,
 988                             weights=None,
 989                             metrics_collections=None,
 990                             updates_collections=None,
 991                             name=None):
 992   """Calculates the mean of the per-class accuracies.
 993 
 994   Calculates the accuracy for each class, then takes the mean of that.
 995 
 996   For estimation of the metric over a stream of data, the function creates an
 997   `update_op` operation that updates the accuracy of each class and returns
 998   them.
 999 
1000   If `weights` is `None`, weights default to 1. Use weights of 0 to mask values.
1001 
1002   Args:
1003     labels: A `Tensor` of ground truth labels with shape [batch size] and of
1004       type `int32` or `int64`. The tensor will be flattened if its rank > 1.
1005     predictions: A `Tensor` of prediction results for semantic labels, whose
1006       shape is [batch size] and type `int32` or `int64`. The tensor will be
1007       flattened if its rank > 1.
1008     num_classes: The possible number of labels the prediction task can
1009       have. This value must be provided, since two variables with shape =
1010       [num_classes] will be allocated.
1011     weights: Optional `Tensor` whose rank is either 0, or the same rank as
1012       `labels`, and must be broadcastable to `labels` (i.e., all dimensions must
1013       be either `1`, or the same as the corresponding `labels` dimension).
1014     metrics_collections: An optional list of collections that
1015       `mean_per_class_accuracy'
1016       should be added to.
1017     updates_collections: An optional list of collections `update_op` should be
1018       added to.
1019     name: An optional variable_scope name.
1020 
1021   Returns:
1022     mean_accuracy: A `Tensor` representing the mean per class accuracy.
1023     update_op: An operation that updates the accuracy tensor.
1024 
1025   Raises:
1026     ValueError: If `predictions` and `labels` have mismatched shapes, or if
1027       `weights` is not `None` and its shape doesn't match `predictions`, or if
1028       either `metrics_collections` or `updates_collections` are not a list or
1029       tuple.
1030     RuntimeError: If eager execution is enabled.
1031   """
1032   if context.executing_eagerly():
1033     raise RuntimeError('tf.metrics.mean_per_class_accuracy is not supported '
1034                        'when eager execution is enabled.')
1035 
1036   with variable_scope.variable_scope(name, 'mean_accuracy',
1037                                      (predictions, labels, weights)):
1038     labels = math_ops.to_int64(labels)
1039 
1040     # Flatten the input if its rank > 1.
1041     if labels.get_shape().ndims > 1:
1042       labels = array_ops.reshape(labels, [-1])
1043 
1044     if predictions.get_shape().ndims > 1:
1045       predictions = array_ops.reshape(predictions, [-1])
1046 
1047     # Check if shape is compatible.
1048     predictions.get_shape().assert_is_compatible_with(labels.get_shape())
1049 
1050     total = metric_variable([num_classes], dtypes.float32, name='total')
1051     count = metric_variable([num_classes], dtypes.float32, name='count')
1052 
1053     ones = array_ops.ones([array_ops.size(labels)], dtypes.float32)
1054 
1055     if labels.dtype != predictions.dtype:
1056       predictions = math_ops.cast(predictions, labels.dtype)
1057     is_correct = math_ops.to_float(math_ops.equal(predictions, labels))
1058 
1059     if weights is not None:
1060       if weights.get_shape().ndims > 1:
1061         weights = array_ops.reshape(weights, [-1])
1062       weights = math_ops.to_float(weights)
1063 
1064       is_correct *= weights
1065       ones *= weights
1066 
1067     update_total_op = state_ops.scatter_add(total, labels, ones)
1068     update_count_op = state_ops.scatter_add(count, labels, is_correct)
1069 
1070     def compute_mean_accuracy(_, count, total):
1071       per_class_accuracy = _safe_div(count, total, None)
1072       mean_accuracy_v = math_ops.reduce_mean(
1073           per_class_accuracy, name='mean_accuracy')
1074       return mean_accuracy_v
1075 
1076     mean_accuracy_v = _aggregate_across_towers(
1077         metrics_collections, compute_mean_accuracy, count, total)
1078 
1079     update_op = _safe_div(update_count_op, update_total_op, name='update_op')
1080     if updates_collections:
1081       ops.add_to_collections(updates_collections, update_op)
1082 
1083     return mean_accuracy_v, update_op

1086 @tf_export('metrics.mean_iou')
1087 def mean_iou(labels,
1088              predictions,
1089              num_classes,
1090              weights=None,
1091              metrics_collections=None,
1092              updates_collections=None,
1093              name=None):
1094   """Calculate per-step mean Intersection-Over-Union (mIOU).
1095 
1096   Mean Intersection-Over-Union is a common evaluation metric for
1097   semantic image segmentation, which first computes the IOU for each
1098   semantic class and then computes the average over classes.
1099   IOU is defined as follows:
1100     IOU = true_positive / (true_positive + false_positive + false_negative).
1101   The predictions are accumulated in a confusion matrix, weighted by `weights`,
1102   and mIOU is then calculated from it.
1103 
1104   For estimation of the metric over a stream of data, the function creates an
1105   `update_op` operation that updates these variables and returns the `mean_iou`.
1106 
1107   If `weights` is `None`, weights default to 1. Use weights of 0 to mask values.
1108 
1109   Args:
1110     labels: A `Tensor` of ground truth labels with shape [batch size] and of
1111       type `int32` or `int64`. The tensor will be flattened if its rank > 1.
1112     predictions: A `Tensor` of prediction results for semantic labels, whose
1113       shape is [batch size] and type `int32` or `int64`. The tensor will be
1114       flattened if its rank > 1.
1115     num_classes: The possible number of labels the prediction task can
1116       have. This value must be provided, since a confusion matrix of
1117       dimension = [num_classes, num_classes] will be allocated.
1118     weights: Optional `Tensor` whose rank is either 0, or the same rank as
1119       `labels`, and must be broadcastable to `labels` (i.e., all dimensions must
1120       be either `1`, or the same as the corresponding `labels` dimension).
1121     metrics_collections: An optional list of collections that `mean_iou`
1122       should be added to.
1123     updates_collections: An optional list of collections `update_op` should be
1124       added to.
1125     name: An optional variable_scope name.
1126 
1127   Returns:
1128     mean_iou: A `Tensor` representing the mean intersection-over-union.
1129     update_op: An operation that increments the confusion matrix.
1130 
1131   Raises:
1132     ValueError: If `predictions` and `labels` have mismatched shapes, or if
1133       `weights` is not `None` and its shape doesn't match `predictions`, or if
1134       either `metrics_collections` or `updates_collections` are not a list or
1135       tuple.
1136     RuntimeError: If eager execution is enabled.
1137   """
1138   if context.executing_eagerly():
1139     raise RuntimeError('tf.metrics.mean_iou is not supported when '
1140                        'eager execution is enabled.')
1141 
1142   with variable_scope.variable_scope(name, 'mean_iou',
1143                                      (predictions, labels, weights)):
1144     # Check if shape is compatible.
1145     predictions.get_shape().assert_is_compatible_with(labels.get_shape())
1146 
1147     total_cm, update_op = _streaming_confusion_matrix(labels, predictions,
1148                                                       num_classes, weights)
1149 
1150     def compute_mean_iou(_, total_cm):
1151       """Compute the mean intersection-over-union via the confusion matrix."""
1152       sum_over_row = math_ops.to_float(math_ops.reduce_sum(total_cm, 0))
1153       sum_over_col = math_ops.to_float(math_ops.reduce_sum(total_cm, 1))
1154       cm_diag = math_ops.to_float(array_ops.diag_part(total_cm))
1155       denominator = sum_over_row + sum_over_col - cm_diag
1156 
1157       # The mean is only computed over classes that appear in the
1158       # label or prediction tensor. If the denominator is 0, we need to
1159       # ignore the class.
1160       num_valid_entries = math_ops.reduce_sum(
1161           math_ops.cast(
1162               math_ops.not_equal(denominator, 0), dtype=dtypes.float32))
1163 
1164       # If the value of the denominator is 0, set it to 1 to avoid
1165       # zero division.
1166       denominator = array_ops.where(
1167           math_ops.greater(denominator, 0), denominator,
1168           array_ops.ones_like(denominator))
1169       iou = math_ops.div(cm_diag, denominator)
1170 
1171       # If the number of valid entries is 0 (no classes) we return 0.
1172       result = array_ops.where(
1173           math_ops.greater(num_valid_entries, 0),
1174           math_ops.reduce_sum(iou, name='mean_iou') / num_valid_entries, 0)
1175       return result
1176 
1177     # TODO(priyag): Use outside_compilation if in TPU context.
1178     mean_iou_v = _aggregate_across_towers(
1179         metrics_collections, compute_mean_iou, total_cm)
1180 
1181     if updates_collections:
1182       ops.add_to_collections(updates_collections, update_op)
1183 
1184     return mean_iou_v, update_op
1185

1317 @tf_export('metrics.mean_tensor')
1318 def mean_tensor(values,
1319                 weights=None,
1320                 metrics_collections=None,
1321                 updates_collections=None,
1322                 name=None):
1323   """Computes the element-wise (weighted) mean of the given tensors.
1324 
1325   In contrast to the `mean` function which returns a scalar with the
1326   mean,  this function returns an average tensor with the same shape as the
1327   input tensors.
1328 
1329   The `mean_tensor` function creates two local variables,
1330   `total_tensor` and `count_tensor` that are used to compute the average of
1331   `values`. This average is ultimately returned as `mean` which is an idempotent
1332   operation that simply divides `total` by `count`.
1333 
1334   For estimation of the metric over a stream of data, the function creates an
1335   `update_op` operation that updates these variables and returns the `mean`.
1336   `update_op` increments `total` with the reduced sum of the product of `values`
1337   and `weights`, and it increments `count` with the reduced sum of `weights`.
1338 
1339   If `weights` is `None`, weights default to 1. Use weights of 0 to mask values.
1340 
1341   Args:
1342     values: A `Tensor` of arbitrary dimensions.
1343     weights: Optional `Tensor` whose rank is either 0, or the same rank as
1344       `values`, and must be broadcastable to `values` (i.e., all dimensions must
1345       be either `1`, or the same as the corresponding `values` dimension).
1346     metrics_collections: An optional list of collections that `mean`
1347       should be added to.
1348     updates_collections: An optional list of collections that `update_op`
1349       should be added to.
1350     name: An optional variable_scope name.
1351 
1352   Returns:
1353     mean: A float `Tensor` representing the current mean, the value of `total`
1354       divided by `count`.
1355     update_op: An operation that increments the `total` and `count` variables
1356       appropriately and whose value matches `mean_value`.
1357 
1358   Raises:
1359     ValueError: If `weights` is not `None` and its shape doesn't match `values`,
1360       or if either `metrics_collections` or `updates_collections` are not a list
1361       or tuple.
1362     RuntimeError: If eager execution is enabled.
1363   """
1364   if context.executing_eagerly():
1365     raise RuntimeError('tf.metrics.mean_tensor is not supported when '
1366                        'eager execution is enabled.')
1367 
1368   with variable_scope.variable_scope(name, 'mean', (values, weights)):
1369     values = math_ops.to_float(values)
1370     total = metric_variable(
1371         values.get_shape(), dtypes.float32, name='total_tensor')
1372     count = metric_variable(
1373         values.get_shape(), dtypes.float32, name='count_tensor')
1374 
1375     num_values = array_ops.ones_like(values)
1376     if weights is not None:
1377       values, _, weights = _remove_squeezable_dimensions(
1378           predictions=values, labels=None, weights=weights)
1379       weights = weights_broadcast_ops.broadcast_weights(
1380           math_ops.to_float(weights), values)
1381       values = math_ops.multiply(values, weights)
1382       num_values = math_ops.multiply(num_values, weights)
1383 
1384     update_total_op = state_ops.assign_add(total, values)
1385     with ops.control_dependencies([values]):
1386       update_count_op = state_ops.assign_add(count, num_values)
1387 
1388     compute_mean = lambda _, t, c: _safe_div(t, c, 'value')
1389 
1390     mean_t = _aggregate_across_towers(
1391         metrics_collections, compute_mean, total, count)
1392 
1393     update_op = _safe_div(update_total_op, update_count_op, 'update_op')
1394     if updates_collections:
1395       ops.add_to_collections(updates_collections, update_op)
1396 
1397     return mean_t, update_op

1454 def _count_condition(values,
1455                      weights=None,
1456                      metrics_collections=None,
1457                      updates_collections=None):
1458   """Sums the weights of cases where the given values are True.
1459 
1460   If `weights` is `None`, weights default to 1. Use weights of 0 to mask values.
1461 
1462   Args:
1463     values: A `bool` `Tensor` of arbitrary size.
1464     weights: Optional `Tensor` whose rank is either 0, or the same rank as
1465       `values`, and must be broadcastable to `values` (i.e., all dimensions must
1466       be either `1`, or the same as the corresponding `values` dimension).
1467     metrics_collections: An optional list of collections that the metric
1468       value variable should be added to.
1469     updates_collections: An optional list of collections that the metric update
1470       ops should be added to.
1471 
1472   Returns:
1473     value_tensor: A `Tensor` representing the current value of the metric.
1474     update_op: An operation that accumulates the error from a batch of data.
1475 
1476   Raises:
1477     ValueError: If `weights` is not `None` and its shape doesn't match `values`,
1478       or if either `metrics_collections` or `updates_collections` are not a list
1479       or tuple.
1480   """
1481   check_ops.assert_type(values, dtypes.bool)
1482   count = metric_variable([], dtypes.float32, name='count')
1483 
1484   values = math_ops.to_float(values)
1485   if weights is not None:
1486     with ops.control_dependencies((check_ops.assert_rank_in(
1487         weights, (0, array_ops.rank(values))),)):
1488       weights = math_ops.to_float(weights)
1489       values = math_ops.multiply(values, weights)

1494   if updates_collections:
1495     ops.add_to_collections(updates_collections, update_op)

1935 @tf_export('metrics.precision')
1936 def precision(labels,
1937               predictions,
1938               weights=None,
1939               metrics_collections=None,
1940               updates_collections=None,
1941               name=None):
1942   """Computes the precision of the predictions with respect to the labels.
1943 
1944   The `precision` function creates two local variables,
1945   `true_positives` and `false_positives`, that are used to compute the
1946   precision. This value is ultimately returned as `precision`, an idempotent
1947   operation that simply divides `true_positives` by the sum of `true_positives`
1948   and `false_positives`.
1949 
1950   For estimation of the metric over a stream of data, the function creates an
1951   `update_op` operation that updates these variables and returns the
1952   `precision`. `update_op` weights each prediction by the corresponding value in
1953   `weights`.
1954 
1955   If `weights` is `None`, weights default to 1. Use weights of 0 to mask values.
1956 
1957   Args:
1958     labels: The ground truth values, a `Tensor` whose dimensions must match
1959       `predictions`. Will be cast to `bool`.
1960     predictions: The predicted values, a `Tensor` of arbitrary dimensions. Will
1961       be cast to `bool`.
1962     weights: Optional `Tensor` whose rank is either 0, or the same rank as
1963       `labels`, and must be broadcastable to `labels` (i.e., all dimensions must
1964       be either `1`, or the same as the corresponding `labels` dimension).
1965     metrics_collections: An optional list of collections that `precision` should
1966       be added to.
1967     updates_collections: An optional list of collections that `update_op` should
1968       be added to.
1969     name: An optional variable_scope name.
1970 
1971   Returns:
1972     precision: Scalar float `Tensor` with the value of `true_positives`
1973       divided by the sum of `true_positives` and `false_positives`.
1974     update_op: `Operation` that increments `true_positives` and
1975       `false_positives` variables appropriately and whose value matches
1976       `precision`.
1977 
1978   Raises:
1979     ValueError: If `predictions` and `labels` have mismatched shapes, or if
1980       `weights` is not `None` and its shape doesn't match `predictions`, or if
1981       either `metrics_collections` or `updates_collections` are not a list or
1982       tuple.
1983     RuntimeError: If eager execution is enabled.
1984   """
1985   if context.executing_eagerly():
1986     raise RuntimeError('tf.metrics.precision is not '
1987                        'supported when eager execution is enabled.')
1988 
1989   with variable_scope.variable_scope(name, 'precision',
1990                                      (predictions, labels, weights)):
1991 
1992     predictions, labels, weights = _remove_squeezable_dimensions(
1993         predictions=math_ops.cast(predictions, dtype=dtypes.bool),
1994         labels=math_ops.cast(labels, dtype=dtypes.bool),
1995         weights=weights)
1996 
1997     true_p, true_positives_update_op = true_positives(
1998         labels,
1999         predictions,
2000         weights,
2001         metrics_collections=None,
2002         updates_collections=None,
2003         name=None)
2004     false_p, false_positives_update_op = false_positives(
2005         labels,
2006         predictions,
2007         weights,
2008         metrics_collections=None,
2009         updates_collections=None,
2010         name=None)
2011 
2012     def compute_precision(tp, fp, name):
2013       return array_ops.where(
2014           math_ops.greater(tp + fp, 0), math_ops.div(tp, tp + fp), 0, name)
2015 
2016     def once_across_towers(_, true_p, false_p):
2017       return compute_precision(true_p, false_p, 'value')
2018 
2019     p = _aggregate_across_towers(metrics_collections, once_across_towers,
2020                                  true_p, false_p)
2021 
2022     update_op = compute_precision(true_positives_update_op,
2023                                   false_positives_update_op, 'update_op')
2024     if updates_collections:
2025       ops.add_to_collections(updates_collections, update_op)
2026 
2027     return p, update_op
2028

2030 @tf_export('metrics.precision_at_thresholds')
2031 def precision_at_thresholds(labels,
2032                             predictions,
2033                             thresholds,
2034                             weights=None,
2035                             metrics_collections=None,
2036                             updates_collections=None,
2037                             name=None):
2038   """Computes precision values for different `thresholds` on `predictions`.
2039 
2040   The `precision_at_thresholds` function creates four local variables,
2041   `true_positives`, `true_negatives`, `false_positives` and `false_negatives`
2042   for various values of thresholds. `precision[i]` is defined as the total
2043   weight of values in `predictions` above `thresholds[i]` whose corresponding
2044   entry in `labels` is `True`, divided by the total weight of values in
2045   `predictions` above `thresholds[i]` (`true_positives[i] / (true_positives[i] +
2046   false_positives[i])`).
2047 
2048   For estimation of the metric over a stream of data, the function creates an
2049   `update_op` operation that updates these variables and returns the
2050   `precision`.
2051 
2052   If `weights` is `None`, weights default to 1. Use weights of 0 to mask values.
2053 
2054   Args:
2055     labels: The ground truth values, a `Tensor` whose dimensions must match
2056       `predictions`. Will be cast to `bool`.
2057     predictions: A floating point `Tensor` of arbitrary shape and whose values
2058       are in the range `[0, 1]`.
2059     thresholds: A python list or tuple of float thresholds in `[0, 1]`.
2060     weights: Optional `Tensor` whose rank is either 0, or the same rank as
2061       `labels`, and must be broadcastable to `labels` (i.e., all dimensions must
2062       be either `1`, or the same as the corresponding `labels` dimension).
2063     metrics_collections: An optional list of collections that `auc` should be
2064       added to.
2065     updates_collections: An optional list of collections that `update_op` should
2066       be added to.
2067     name: An optional variable_scope name.
2068 
2069   Returns:
2070     precision: A float `Tensor` of shape `[len(thresholds)]`.
2071     update_op: An operation that increments the `true_positives`,
2072       `true_negatives`, `false_positives` and `false_negatives` variables that
2073       are used in the computation of `precision`.
2074 
2075   Raises:
2076     ValueError: If `predictions` and `labels` have mismatched shapes, or if
2077       `weights` is not `None` and its shape doesn't match `predictions`, or if
2078       either `metrics_collections` or `updates_collections` are not a list or
2079       tuple.
2080     RuntimeError: If eager execution is enabled.
2081   """
2082   if context.executing_eagerly():
2083     raise RuntimeError('tf.metrics.precision_at_thresholds is not '
2084                        'supported when eager execution is enabled.')
2085 
2086   with variable_scope.variable_scope(name, 'precision_at_thresholds',
2087                                      (predictions, labels, weights)):
2088     values, update_ops = _confusion_matrix_at_thresholds(
2089         labels, predictions, thresholds, weights, includes=('tp', 'fp'))
2090 
2091     # Avoid division by zero.
2092     epsilon = 1e-7
2093 
2094     def compute_precision(tp, fp, name):
2095       return math_ops.div(tp, epsilon + tp + fp, name='precision_' + name)
2096 
2097     def precision_across_towers(_, values):
2098       return compute_precision(values['tp'], values['fp'], 'value')
2099 
2100     prec = _aggregate_across_towers(
2101         metrics_collections, precision_across_towers, values)
2102 
2103     update_op = compute_precision(update_ops['tp'], update_ops['fp'],
2104                                   'update_op')
2105     if updates_collections:
2106       ops.add_to_collections(updates_collections, update_op)
2107 
2108     return prec, update_op
2109

2185     def compute_recall(true_p, false_n, name):
2186       return array_ops.where(
2187           math_ops.greater(true_p + false_n, 0),
2188           math_ops.div(true_p, true_p + false_n), 0, name)
2189 
2190     def once_across_towers(_, true_p, false_n):
2191       return compute_recall(true_p, false_n, 'value')
2192 
2193     rec = _aggregate_across_towers(
2194         metrics_collections, once_across_towers, true_p, false_n)
2195 
2196     update_op = compute_recall(true_positives_update_op,
2197                                false_negatives_update_op, 'update_op')
2198     if updates_collections:
2199       ops.add_to_collections(updates_collections, update_op)
2200 
2201     return rec, update_op
2202

2204 def _at_k_name(name, k=None, class_id=None):
2205   if k is not None:
2206     name = '%s_at_%d' % (name, k)
2207   else:
2208     name = '%s_at_k' % (name)
2209   if class_id is not None:
2210     name = '%s_class%d' % (name, class_id)
2211   return name

2214 def _select_class_id(ids, selected_id):
2215   """Filter all but `selected_id` out of `ids`.
2216 
2217   Args:
2218     ids: `int64` `Tensor` or `SparseTensor` of IDs.
2219     selected_id: Int id to select.
2220 
2221   Returns:
2222     `SparseTensor` of same dimensions as `ids`. This contains only the entries
2223     equal to `selected_id`.
2224   """
2225   ids = sparse_tensor.convert_to_tensor_or_sparse_tensor(ids)
2226   if isinstance(ids, sparse_tensor.SparseTensor):
2227     return sparse_ops.sparse_retain(ids, math_ops.equal(ids.values,
2228                                                         selected_id))
2229 
2230   # TODO(ptucker): Make this more efficient, maybe add a sparse version of
2231   # tf.equal and tf.reduce_any?
2232 
2233   # Shape of filled IDs is the same as `ids` with the last dim collapsed to 1.
2234   ids_shape = array_ops.shape(ids, out_type=dtypes.int64)
2235   ids_last_dim = array_ops.size(ids_shape) - 1
2236   filled_selected_id_shape = math_ops.reduced_shape(ids_shape,
2237                                                     array_ops.reshape(
2238                                                         ids_last_dim, [1]))
2239 
2240   # Intersect `ids` with the selected ID.
2241   filled_selected_id = array_ops.fill(filled_selected_id_shape,
2242                                       math_ops.to_int64(selected_id))
2243   result = sets.set_intersection(filled_selected_id, ids)
2244   return sparse_tensor.SparseTensor(
2245       indices=result.indices, values=result.values, dense_shape=ids_shape)

2248 def _maybe_select_class_id(labels, predictions_idx, selected_id=None):
2249   """If class ID is specified, filter all other classes.
2250 
2251   Args:
2252     labels: `int64` `Tensor` or `SparseTensor` with shape
2253       [D1, ... DN, num_labels], where N >= 1 and num_labels is the number of
2254       target classes for the associated prediction. Commonly, N=1 and `labels`
2255       has shape [batch_size, num_labels]. [D1, ... DN] must match
2256       `predictions_idx`.
2257     predictions_idx: `int64` `Tensor` of class IDs, with shape [D1, ... DN, k]
2258       where N >= 1. Commonly, N=1 and `predictions_idx` has shape
2259       [batch size, k].
2260     selected_id: Int id to select.
2261 
2262   Returns:
2263     Tuple of `labels` and `predictions_idx`, possibly with classes removed.
2264   """
2265   if selected_id is None:
2266     return labels, predictions_idx
2267   return (_select_class_id(labels, selected_id),
2268           _select_class_id(predictions_idx, selected_id))

2271 def _sparse_true_positive_at_k(labels,
2272                                predictions_idx,
2273                                class_id=None,
2274                                weights=None,
2275                                name=None):
2276   """Calculates true positives for recall@k and precision@k.
2277 
2278   If `class_id` is specified, calculate binary true positives for `class_id`
2279       only.
2280   If `class_id` is not specified, calculate metrics for `k` predicted vs
2281       `n` label classes, where `n` is the 2nd dimension of `labels_sparse`.
2282 
2283   Args:
2284     labels: `int64` `Tensor` or `SparseTensor` with shape
2285       [D1, ... DN, num_labels], where N >= 1 and num_labels is the number of
2286       target classes for the associated prediction. Commonly, N=1 and `labels`
2287       has shape [batch_size, num_labels]. [D1, ... DN] must match
2288       `predictions_idx`.
2289     predictions_idx: 1-D or higher `int64` `Tensor` with last dimension `k`,
2290       top `k` predicted classes. For rank `n`, the first `n-1` dimensions must
2291       match `labels`.
2292     class_id: Class for which we want binary metrics.
2293     weights: `Tensor` whose rank is either 0, or n-1, where n is the rank of
2294       `labels`. If the latter, it must be broadcastable to `labels` (i.e., all
2295       dimensions must be either `1`, or the same as the corresponding `labels`
2296       dimension).
2297     name: Name of operation.
2298 
2299   Returns:
2300     A [D1, ... DN] `Tensor` of true positive counts.
2301   """
2302   with ops.name_scope(name, 'true_positives',
2303                       (predictions_idx, labels, weights)):
2304     labels, predictions_idx = _maybe_select_class_id(labels, predictions_idx,
2305                                                      class_id)
2306     tp = sets.set_size(sets.set_intersection(predictions_idx, labels))
2307     tp = math_ops.to_double(tp)
2308     if weights is not None:
2309       with ops.control_dependencies((weights_broadcast_ops.assert_broadcastable(
2310           weights, tp),)):
2311         weights = math_ops.to_double(weights)
2312         tp = math_ops.multiply(tp, weights)
2313     return tp

2462 @tf_export('metrics.recall_at_k')
2463 def recall_at_k(labels,
2464                 predictions,
2465                 k,
2466                 class_id=None,
2467                 weights=None,
2468                 metrics_collections=None,
2469                 updates_collections=None,
2470                 name=None):
2471   """Computes recall@k of the predictions with respect to sparse labels.
2472 
2473   If `class_id` is specified, we calculate recall by considering only the
2474       entries in the batch for which `class_id` is in the label, and computing
2475       the fraction of them for which `class_id` is in the top-k `predictions`.
2476   If `class_id` is not specified, we'll calculate recall as how often on
2477       average a class among the labels of a batch entry is in the top-k
2478       `predictions`.
2479 
2480   `sparse_recall_at_k` creates two local variables,
2481   `true_positive_at_<k>` and `false_negative_at_<k>`, that are used to compute
2482   the recall_at_k frequency. This frequency is ultimately returned as
2483   `recall_at_<k>`: an idempotent operation that simply divides
2484   `true_positive_at_<k>` by total (`true_positive_at_<k>` +
2485   `false_negative_at_<k>`).
2486 
2487   For estimation of the metric over a stream of data, the function creates an
2488   `update_op` operation that updates these variables and returns the
2489   `recall_at_<k>`. Internally, a `top_k` operation computes a `Tensor`
2490   indicating the top `k` `predictions`. Set operations applied to `top_k` and
2491   `labels` calculate the true positives and false negatives weighted by
2492   `weights`. Then `update_op` increments `true_positive_at_<k>` and
2493   `false_negative_at_<k>` using these values.
2494 
2495   If `weights` is `None`, weights default to 1. Use weights of 0 to mask values.
2496 
2497   Args:
2498     labels: `int64` `Tensor` or `SparseTensor` with shape
2499       [D1, ... DN, num_labels] or [D1, ... DN], where the latter implies
2500       num_labels=1. N >= 1 and num_labels is the number of target classes for
2501       the associated prediction. Commonly, N=1 and `labels` has shape
2502       [batch_size, num_labels]. [D1, ... DN] must match `predictions`. Values
2503       should be in range [0, num_classes), where num_classes is the last
2504       dimension of `predictions`. Values outside this range always count
2505       towards `false_negative_at_<k>`.
2506     predictions: Float `Tensor` with shape [D1, ... DN, num_classes] where
2507       N >= 1. Commonly, N=1 and predictions has shape [batch size, num_classes].
2508       The final dimension contains the logit values for each class. [D1, ... DN]
2509       must match `labels`.
2510     k: Integer, k for @k metric.
2511     class_id: Integer class ID for which we want binary metrics. This should be
2512       in range [0, num_classes), where num_classes is the last dimension of
2513       `predictions`. If class_id is outside this range, the method returns NAN.
2514     weights: `Tensor` whose rank is either 0, or n-1, where n is the rank of
2515       `labels`. If the latter, it must be broadcastable to `labels` (i.e., all
2516       dimensions must be either `1`, or the same as the corresponding `labels`
2517       dimension).
2518     metrics_collections: An optional list of collections that values should
2519       be added to.
2520     updates_collections: An optional list of collections that updates should
2521       be added to.
2522     name: Name of new update operation, and namespace for other dependent ops.
2523 
2524   Returns:
2525     recall: Scalar `float64` `Tensor` with the value of `true_positives` divided
2526       by the sum of `true_positives` and `false_negatives`.
2527     update_op: `Operation` that increments `true_positives` and
2528       `false_negatives` variables appropriately, and whose value matches
2529       `recall`.
2530 
2531   Raises:
2532     ValueError: If `weights` is not `None` and its shape doesn't match
2533     `predictions`, or if either `metrics_collections` or `updates_collections`
2534     are not a list or tuple.
2535     RuntimeError: If eager execution is enabled.
2536   """
2537   if context.executing_eagerly():
2538     raise RuntimeError('tf.metrics.recall_at_k is not '
2539                        'supported when eager execution is enabled.')
2540 
2541   with ops.name_scope(name, _at_k_name('recall', k, class_id=class_id),
2542                       (predictions, labels, weights)) as scope:
2543     _, top_k_idx = nn.top_k(predictions, k)
2544     return recall_at_top_k(
2545         labels=labels,
2546         predictions_idx=top_k_idx,
2547         k=k,
2548         class_id=class_id,
2549         weights=weights,
2550         metrics_collections=metrics_collections,
2551         updates_collections=updates_collections,
2552         name=scope)
2553
