2555 @tf_export('metrics.recall_at_top_k')
2556 def recall_at_top_k(labels,
2557                     predictions_idx,
2558                     k=None,
2559                     class_id=None,
2560                     weights=None,
2561                     metrics_collections=None,
2562                     updates_collections=None,
2563                     name=None):
2564   """Computes recall@k of top-k predictions with respect to sparse labels.
2565 
2566   Differs from `recall_at_k` in that predictions must be in the form of top `k`
2567   class indices, whereas `recall_at_k` expects logits. Refer to `recall_at_k`
2568   for more details.
2569 
2570   Args:
2571     labels: `int64` `Tensor` or `SparseTensor` with shape
2572       [D1, ... DN, num_labels] or [D1, ... DN], where the latter implies
2573       num_labels=1. N >= 1 and num_labels is the number of target classes for
2574       the associated prediction. Commonly, N=1 and `labels` has shape
2575       [batch_size, num_labels]. [D1, ... DN] must match `predictions`. Values
2576       should be in range [0, num_classes), where num_classes is the last
2577       dimension of `predictions`. Values outside this range always count
2578       towards `false_negative_at_<k>`.
2579     predictions_idx: Integer `Tensor` with shape [D1, ... DN, k] where N >= 1.
2580       Commonly, N=1 and predictions has shape [batch size, k]. The final
2581       dimension contains the top `k` predicted class indices. [D1, ... DN] must
2582       match `labels`.
2583     k: Integer, k for @k metric. Only used for the default op name.
2584     class_id: Integer class ID for which we want binary metrics. This should be
2585       in range [0, num_classes), where num_classes is the last dimension of
2586       `predictions`. If class_id is outside this range, the method returns NAN.
2587     weights: `Tensor` whose rank is either 0, or n-1, where n is the rank of
2588       `labels`. If the latter, it must be broadcastable to `labels` (i.e., all
2589       dimensions must be either `1`, or the same as the corresponding `labels`
2590       dimension).
2591     metrics_collections: An optional list of collections that values should
2592       be added to.
2593     updates_collections: An optional list of collections that updates should
2594       be added to.
2595     name: Name of new update operation, and namespace for other dependent ops.
2596 
2597   Returns:
2598     recall: Scalar `float64` `Tensor` with the value of `true_positives` divided
2599       by the sum of `true_positives` and `false_negatives`.
2600     update_op: `Operation` that increments `true_positives` and
2601       `false_negatives` variables appropriately, and whose value matches
2602       `recall`.
2603 
2604   Raises:
2605     ValueError: If `weights` is not `None` and its shape doesn't match
2606     `predictions`, or if either `metrics_collections` or `updates_collections`
2607     are not a list or tuple.
2608   """
2609   with ops.name_scope(name, _at_k_name('recall', k, class_id=class_id),
2610                       (predictions_idx, labels, weights)) as scope:
2611     labels = _maybe_expand_labels(labels, predictions_idx)
2612     top_k_idx = math_ops.to_int64(predictions_idx)
2613     tp, tp_update = _streaming_sparse_true_positive_at_k(
2614         predictions_idx=top_k_idx,
2615         labels=labels,
2616         k=k,
2617         class_id=class_id,
2618         weights=weights)
2619     fn, fn_update = _streaming_sparse_false_negative_at_k(
2620         predictions_idx=top_k_idx,
2621         labels=labels,
2622         k=k,
2623         class_id=class_id,
2624         weights=weights)
2625 
2626     def compute_recall(_, tp, fn):
2627       return math_ops.div(tp, math_ops.add(tp, fn), name=scope)
2628 
2629     metric = _aggregate_across_towers(
2630         metrics_collections, compute_recall, tp, fn)
2631 
2632     update = math_ops.div(
2633         tp_update, math_ops.add(tp_update, fn_update), name='update')
2634     if updates_collections:
2635       ops.add_to_collections(updates_collections, update)
2636     return metric, update

2639 @tf_export('metrics.recall_at_thresholds')
2640 def recall_at_thresholds(labels,
2641                          predictions,
2642                          thresholds,
2643                          weights=None,
2644                          metrics_collections=None,
2645                          updates_collections=None,
2646                          name=None):
2647   """Computes various recall values for different `thresholds` on `predictions`.
2648 
2649   The `recall_at_thresholds` function creates four local variables,
2650   `true_positives`, `true_negatives`, `false_positives` and `false_negatives`
2651   for various values of thresholds. `recall[i]` is defined as the total weight
2652   of values in `predictions` above `thresholds[i]` whose corresponding entry in
2653   `labels` is `True`, divided by the total weight of `True` values in `labels`
2654   (`true_positives[i] / (true_positives[i] + false_negatives[i])`).
2655 
2656   For estimation of the metric over a stream of data, the function creates an
2657   `update_op` operation that updates these variables and returns the `recall`.
2658 
2659   If `weights` is `None`, weights default to 1. Use weights of 0 to mask values.
2660 
2661   Args:
2662     labels: The ground truth values, a `Tensor` whose dimensions must match
2663       `predictions`. Will be cast to `bool`.
2664     predictions: A floating point `Tensor` of arbitrary shape and whose values
2665       are in the range `[0, 1]`.
2666     thresholds: A python list or tuple of float thresholds in `[0, 1]`.
2667     weights: Optional `Tensor` whose rank is either 0, or the same rank as
2668       `labels`, and must be broadcastable to `labels` (i.e., all dimensions must
2669       be either `1`, or the same as the corresponding `labels` dimension).
2670     metrics_collections: An optional list of collections that `recall` should be
2671       added to.
2672     updates_collections: An optional list of collections that `update_op` should
2673       be added to.
2674     name: An optional variable_scope name.
2675 
2676   Returns:
2677     recall: A float `Tensor` of shape `[len(thresholds)]`.
2678     update_op: An operation that increments the `true_positives`,
2679       `true_negatives`, `false_positives` and `false_negatives` variables that
2680       are used in the computation of `recall`.
2681 
2682   Raises:
2683     ValueError: If `predictions` and `labels` have mismatched shapes, or if
2684       `weights` is not `None` and its shape doesn't match `predictions`, or if
2685       either `metrics_collections` or `updates_collections` are not a list or
2686       tuple.
2687     RuntimeError: If eager execution is enabled.
2688   """
2689   if context.executing_eagerly():
2690     raise RuntimeError('tf.metrics.recall_at_thresholds is not '
2691                        'supported when eager execution is enabled.')
2692 
2693   with variable_scope.variable_scope(name, 'recall_at_thresholds',
2694                                      (predictions, labels, weights)):
2695     values, update_ops = _confusion_matrix_at_thresholds(
2696         labels, predictions, thresholds, weights, includes=('tp', 'fn'))
2697 
2698     # Avoid division by zero.
2699     epsilon = 1e-7
2700 
2701     def compute_recall(tp, fn, name):
2702       return math_ops.div(tp, epsilon + tp + fn, name='recall_' + name)
2703 
2704     def recall_across_towers(_, values):
2705       return compute_recall(values['tp'], values['fn'], 'value')
2706 
2707     rec = _aggregate_across_towers(
2708         metrics_collections, recall_across_towers, values)
2709 
2710     update_op = compute_recall(update_ops['tp'], update_ops['fn'], 'update_op')
2711     if updates_collections:
2712       ops.add_to_collections(updates_collections, update_op)
2713 
2714     return rec, update_op

2717 @tf_export('metrics.root_mean_squared_error')
2718 def root_mean_squared_error(labels,
2719                             predictions,
2720                             weights=None,
2721                             metrics_collections=None,
2722                             updates_collections=None,
2723                             name=None):
2724   """Computes the root mean squared error between the labels and predictions.
2725 
2726   The `root_mean_squared_error` function creates two local variables,
2727   `total` and `count` that are used to compute the root mean squared error.
2728   This average is weighted by `weights`, and it is ultimately returned as
2729   `root_mean_squared_error`: an idempotent operation that takes the square root
2730   of the division of `total` by `count`.
2731 
2732   For estimation of the metric over a stream of data, the function creates an
2733   `update_op` operation that updates these variables and returns the
2734   `root_mean_squared_error`. Internally, a `squared_error` operation computes
2735   the element-wise square of the difference between `predictions` and `labels`.
2736   Then `update_op` increments `total` with the reduced sum of the product of
2737   `weights` and `squared_error`, and it increments `count` with the reduced sum
2738   of `weights`.
2739 
2740   If `weights` is `None`, weights default to 1. Use weights of 0 to mask values.
2741 
2742   Args:
2743     labels: A `Tensor` of the same shape as `predictions`.
2744     predictions: A `Tensor` of arbitrary shape.
2745     weights: Optional `Tensor` whose rank is either 0, or the same rank as
2746       `labels`, and must be broadcastable to `labels` (i.e., all dimensions must
2747       be either `1`, or the same as the corresponding `labels` dimension).
2748     metrics_collections: An optional list of collections that
2749       `root_mean_squared_error` should be added to.
2750     updates_collections: An optional list of collections that `update_op` should
2751       be added to.
2752     name: An optional variable_scope name.
2753 
2754   Returns:
2755     root_mean_squared_error: A `Tensor` representing the current mean, the value
2756       of `total` divided by `count`.
2757     update_op: An operation that increments the `total` and `count` variables
2758       appropriately and whose value matches `root_mean_squared_error`.
2759 
2760   Raises:
2761     ValueError: If `predictions` and `labels` have mismatched shapes, or if
2762       `weights` is not `None` and its shape doesn't match `predictions`, or if
2763       either `metrics_collections` or `updates_collections` are not a list or
2764       tuple.
2765     RuntimeError: If eager execution is enabled.
2766   """
2767   if context.executing_eagerly():
2768     raise RuntimeError('tf.metrics.root_mean_squared_error is not '
2769                        'supported when eager execution is enabled.')
2770 
2771   predictions, labels, weights = _remove_squeezable_dimensions(
2772       predictions=predictions, labels=labels, weights=weights)
2773   mse, update_mse_op = mean_squared_error(labels, predictions, weights, None,
2774                                           None, name or
2775                                           'root_mean_squared_error')
2776 
2777   once_across_towers = lambda _, mse: math_ops.sqrt(mse)
2778   rmse = _aggregate_across_towers(metrics_collections, once_across_towers, mse)
2779 
2780   update_rmse_op = math_ops.sqrt(update_mse_op)
2781   if updates_collections:
2782     ops.add_to_collections(updates_collections, update_rmse_op)
2783 
2784   return rmse, update_rmse_op

2787 @tf_export('metrics.sensitivity_at_specificity')
2788 def sensitivity_at_specificity(labels,
2789                                predictions,
2790                                specificity,
2791                                weights=None,
2792                                num_thresholds=200,
2793                                metrics_collections=None,
2794                                updates_collections=None,
2795                                name=None):
2796   """Computes the specificity at a given sensitivity.
2797 
2798   The `sensitivity_at_specificity` function creates four local
2799   variables, `true_positives`, `true_negatives`, `false_positives` and
2800   `false_negatives` that are used to compute the sensitivity at the given
2801   specificity value. The threshold for the given specificity value is computed
2802   and used to evaluate the corresponding sensitivity.
2803 
2804   For estimation of the metric over a stream of data, the function creates an
2805   `update_op` operation that updates these variables and returns the
2806   `sensitivity`. `update_op` increments the `true_positives`, `true_negatives`,
2807   `false_positives` and `false_negatives` counts with the weight of each case
2808   found in the `predictions` and `labels`.
2809 
2810   If `weights` is `None`, weights default to 1. Use weights of 0 to mask values.
2811 
2812   For additional information about specificity and sensitivity, see the
2813   following: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sensitivity_and_specificity
2814 
2815   Args:
2816     labels: The ground truth values, a `Tensor` whose dimensions must match
2817       `predictions`. Will be cast to `bool`.
2818     predictions: A floating point `Tensor` of arbitrary shape and whose values
2819       are in the range `[0, 1]`.
2820     specificity: A scalar value in range `[0, 1]`.
2821     weights: Optional `Tensor` whose rank is either 0, or the same rank as
2822       `labels`, and must be broadcastable to `labels` (i.e., all dimensions must
2823       be either `1`, or the same as the corresponding `labels` dimension).
2824     num_thresholds: The number of thresholds to use for matching the given
2825       specificity.
2826     metrics_collections: An optional list of collections that `sensitivity`
2827       should be added to.
2828     updates_collections: An optional list of collections that `update_op` should
2829       be added to.
2830     name: An optional variable_scope name.
2831 
2832   Returns:
2833     sensitivity: A scalar `Tensor` representing the sensitivity at the given
2834       `specificity` value.
2835     update_op: An operation that increments the `true_positives`,
2836       `true_negatives`, `false_positives` and `false_negatives` variables
2837       appropriately and whose value matches `sensitivity`.
2838 
2839   Raises:
2840     ValueError: If `predictions` and `labels` have mismatched shapes, if
2841       `weights` is not `None` and its shape doesn't match `predictions`, or if
2842       `specificity` is not between 0 and 1, or if either `metrics_collections`
2843       or `updates_collections` are not a list or tuple.
2844     RuntimeError: If eager execution is enabled.
2845   """
2846   if context.executing_eagerly():
2847     raise RuntimeError('tf.metrics.sensitivity_at_specificity is not '
2848                        'supported when eager execution is enabled.')
2849 
2850   if specificity < 0 or specificity > 1:
2851     raise ValueError('`specificity` must be in the range [0, 1].')
2852 
2853   with variable_scope.variable_scope(name, 'sensitivity_at_specificity',
2854                                      (predictions, labels, weights)):
2855     kepsilon = 1e-7  # to account for floating point imprecisions
2856     thresholds = [
2857         (i + 1) * 1.0 / (num_thresholds - 1) for i in range(num_thresholds - 2)
2858     ]
2859     thresholds = [0.0 - kepsilon] + thresholds + [1.0 + kepsilon]
2860 
2861     values, update_ops = _confusion_matrix_at_thresholds(
2862         labels, predictions, thresholds, weights)
2863 
2864     def compute_sensitivity_at_specificity(tp, tn, fp, fn, name):
2865       specificities = math_ops.div(tn, tn + fp + kepsilon)
2866       tf_index = math_ops.argmin(math_ops.abs(specificities - specificity), 0)
2867       tf_index = math_ops.cast(tf_index, dtypes.int32)
2868 
2869       # Now, we have the implicit threshold, so compute the sensitivity:
2870       return math_ops.div(tp[tf_index], tp[tf_index] + fn[tf_index] + kepsilon,
2871                           name)
2872 
2873     def sensitivity_across_towers(_, values):
2874       return compute_sensitivity_at_specificity(
2875           values['tp'], values['tn'], values['fp'], values['fn'], 'value')
2876 
2877     sensitivity = _aggregate_across_towers(
2878         metrics_collections, sensitivity_across_towers, values)
2879 
2880     update_op = compute_sensitivity_at_specificity(
2881         update_ops['tp'], update_ops['tn'], update_ops['fp'], update_ops['fn'],
2882         'update_op')
2883     if updates_collections:
2884       ops.add_to_collections(updates_collections, update_op)
2885 
2886     return sensitivity, update_op

2889 def _expand_and_tile(tensor, multiple, dim=0, name=None):
2890   """Slice `tensor` shape in 2, then tile along the sliced dimension.
2891 
2892   A new dimension is inserted in shape of `tensor` before `dim`, then values are
2893   tiled `multiple` times along the new dimension.
2894 
2895   Args:
2896     tensor: Input `Tensor` or `SparseTensor`.
2897     multiple: Integer, number of times to tile.
2898     dim: Integer, dimension along which to tile.
2899     name: Name of operation.
2900 
2901   Returns:
2902     `Tensor` result of expanding and tiling `tensor`.
2903 
2904   Raises:
2905     ValueError: if `multiple` is less than 1, or `dim` is not in
2906     `[-rank(tensor), rank(tensor)]`.
2907   """
2908   if multiple < 1:
2909     raise ValueError('Invalid multiple %s, must be > 0.' % multiple)
2910   with ops.name_scope(name, 'expand_and_tile',
2911                       (tensor, multiple, dim)) as scope:
2912     # Sparse.
2913     tensor = sparse_tensor.convert_to_tensor_or_sparse_tensor(tensor)
2914     if isinstance(tensor, sparse_tensor.SparseTensor):
2915       if dim < 0:
2916         expand_dims = array_ops.reshape(
2917             array_ops.size(tensor.dense_shape) + dim, [1])
2918       else:
2919         expand_dims = [dim]
2920       expanded_shape = array_ops.concat(
2921           (array_ops.slice(tensor.dense_shape, [0], expand_dims), [1],
2922            array_ops.slice(tensor.dense_shape, expand_dims, [-1])),
2923           0,
2924           name='expanded_shape')
2925       expanded = sparse_ops.sparse_reshape(
2926           tensor, shape=expanded_shape, name='expand')
2927       if multiple == 1:
2928         return expanded
2929       return sparse_ops.sparse_concat(
2930           dim - 1 if dim < 0 else dim, [expanded] * multiple, name=scope)
2931 
2932     # Dense.
2933     expanded = array_ops.expand_dims(
2934         tensor, dim if (dim >= 0) else (dim - 1), name='expand')
2935     if multiple == 1:
2936       return expanded
2937     ones = array_ops.ones_like(array_ops.shape(tensor))
2938     tile_multiples = array_ops.concat(
2939         (ones[:dim], (multiple,), ones[dim:]), 0, name='multiples')
2940     return array_ops.tile(expanded, tile_multiples, name=scope)

2943 def _num_relevant(labels, k):
2944   """Computes number of relevant values for each row in labels.
2945 
2946   For labels with shape [D1, ... DN, num_labels], this is the minimum of
2947   `num_labels` and `k`.
2948 
2949   Args:
2950     labels: `int64` `Tensor` or `SparseTensor` with shape
2951       [D1, ... DN, num_labels], where N >= 1 and num_labels is the number of
2952       target classes for the associated prediction. Commonly, N=1 and `labels`
2953       has shape [batch_size, num_labels].
2954     k: Integer, k for @k metric.
2955 
2956   Returns:
2957     Integer `Tensor` of shape [D1, ... DN], where each value is the number of
2958     relevant values for that row.
2959 
2960   Raises:
2961     ValueError: if inputs have invalid dtypes or values.
2962   """
2963   if k < 1:
2964     raise ValueError('Invalid k=%s.' % k)
2965   with ops.name_scope(None, 'num_relevant', (labels,)) as scope:
2966     # For SparseTensor, calculate separate count for each row.
2967     labels = sparse_tensor.convert_to_tensor_or_sparse_tensor(labels)
2968     if isinstance(labels, sparse_tensor.SparseTensor):
2969       return math_ops.minimum(sets.set_size(labels), k, name=scope)
2970 
2971     # For dense Tensor, calculate scalar count based on last dimension, and
2972     # tile across labels shape.
2973     labels_shape = array_ops.shape(labels)
2974     labels_size = labels_shape[-1]
2975     num_relevant_scalar = math_ops.minimum(labels_size, k)
2976     return array_ops.fill(labels_shape[0:-1], num_relevant_scalar, name=scope)

2979 def _sparse_average_precision_at_top_k(labels, predictions_idx):
2980   """Computes average precision@k of predictions with respect to sparse labels.
2981 
2982   From en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Information_retrieval#Average_precision, formula
2983   for each row is:
2984 
2985     AveP = sum_{i=1...k} P_{i} * rel_{i} / num_relevant_items
2986 
2987   A "row" is the elements in dimension [D1, ... DN] of `predictions_idx`,
2988   `labels`, and the result `Tensors`. In the common case, this is [batch_size].
2989   Each row of the results contains the average precision for that row.
2990 
2991   Args:
2992     labels: `int64` `Tensor` or `SparseTensor` with shape
2993       [D1, ... DN, num_labels] or [D1, ... DN], where the latter implies
2994       num_labels=1. N >= 1 and num_labels is the number of target classes for
2995       the associated prediction. Commonly, N=1 and `labels` has shape
2996       [batch_size, num_labels]. [D1, ... DN] must match `predictions_idx`.
2997       Values should be in range [0, num_classes).
2998     predictions_idx: Integer `Tensor` with shape [D1, ... DN, k] where N >= 1.
2999       Commonly, N=1 and `predictions_idx` has shape [batch size, k]. The final
3000       dimension must be set and contains the top `k` predicted class indices.
3001       [D1, ... DN] must match `labels`. Values should be in range
3002       [0, num_classes).
3003 
3004   Returns:
3005     `float64` `Tensor` of shape [D1, ... DN], where each value is the average
3006     precision for that row.
3007 
3008   Raises:
3009     ValueError: if the last dimension of predictions_idx is not set.
3010   """
3011   with ops.name_scope(None, 'average_precision',
3012                       (predictions_idx, labels)) as scope:
3013     predictions_idx = math_ops.to_int64(predictions_idx, name='predictions_idx')
3014     if predictions_idx.get_shape().ndims == 0:
3015       raise ValueError('The rank of predictions_idx must be at least 1.')
3016     k = predictions_idx.get_shape().as_list()[-1]
3017     if k is None:
3018       raise ValueError('The last dimension of predictions_idx must be set.')
3019     labels = _maybe_expand_labels(labels, predictions_idx)
3020 
3021     # Expand dims to produce [D1, ... DN, k, 1] tensor. This gives us a separate
3022     # prediction for each k, so we can calculate separate true positive values
3023     # for each k.
3024     predictions_idx_per_k = array_ops.expand_dims(
3025         predictions_idx, -1, name='predictions_idx_per_k')
3026 
3027     # Replicate labels k times to produce [D1, ... DN, k, num_labels] tensor.
3028     labels_per_k = _expand_and_tile(
3029         labels, multiple=k, dim=-1, name='labels_per_k')
3030 
3031     # The following tensors are all of shape [D1, ... DN, k], containing values
3032     # per row, per k value.
3033     # `relevant_per_k` (int32) - Relevance indicator, 1 if the prediction at
3034     #     that k value is correct, 0 otherwise. This is the "rel_{i}" term from
3035     #     the formula above.
3036     # `tp_per_k` (int32) - True positive counts.
3037     # `retrieved_per_k` (int32) - Number of predicted values at each k. This is
3038     #     the precision denominator.
3039     # `precision_per_k` (float64) - Precision at each k. This is the "P_{i}"
3040     #     term from the formula above.
3041     # `relevant_precision_per_k` (float64) - Relevant precisions; i.e.,
3042     #     precisions at all k for which relevance indicator is true.
3043     relevant_per_k = _sparse_true_positive_at_k(
3044         labels_per_k, predictions_idx_per_k, name='relevant_per_k')
3045     tp_per_k = math_ops.cumsum(relevant_per_k, axis=-1, name='tp_per_k')
3046     retrieved_per_k = math_ops.cumsum(
3047         array_ops.ones_like(relevant_per_k), axis=-1, name='retrieved_per_k')
3048     precision_per_k = math_ops.div(
3049         math_ops.to_double(tp_per_k),
3050         math_ops.to_double(retrieved_per_k),
3051         name='precision_per_k')
3052     relevant_precision_per_k = math_ops.multiply(
3053         precision_per_k,
3054         math_ops.to_double(relevant_per_k),
3055         name='relevant_precision_per_k')
3056 
3057     # Reduce along k dimension to get the sum, yielding a [D1, ... DN] tensor.
3058     precision_sum = math_ops.reduce_sum(
3059         relevant_precision_per_k, reduction_indices=(-1,), name='precision_sum')
3060 
3061     # Divide by number of relevant items to get average precision. These are
3062     # the "num_relevant_items" and "AveP" terms from the formula above.
3063     num_relevant_items = math_ops.to_double(_num_relevant(labels, k))
3064     return math_ops.div(precision_sum, num_relevant_items, name=scope)

3067 def _streaming_sparse_average_precision_at_top_k(labels,
3068                                                  predictions_idx,
3069                                                  weights=None,
3070                                                  metrics_collections=None,
3071                                                  updates_collections=None,
3072                                                  name=None):
3073   """Computes average precision@k of predictions with respect to sparse labels.
3074 
3075   `sparse_average_precision_at_top_k` creates two local variables,
3076   `average_precision_at_<k>/total` and `average_precision_at_<k>/max`, that
3077   are used to compute the frequency. This frequency is ultimately returned as
3078   `average_precision_at_<k>`: an idempotent operation that simply divides
3079   `average_precision_at_<k>/total` by `average_precision_at_<k>/max`.
3080 
3081   For estimation of the metric over a stream of data, the function creates an
3082   `update_op` operation that updates these variables and returns the
3083   `precision_at_<k>`. Set operations applied to `top_k` and `labels` calculate
3084   the true positives and false positives weighted by `weights`. Then `update_op`
3085   increments `true_positive_at_<k>` and `false_positive_at_<k>` using these
3086   values.
3087 
3088   If `weights` is `None`, weights default to 1. Use weights of 0 to mask values.
3089 
3090   Args:
3091     labels: `int64` `Tensor` or `SparseTensor` with shape
3092       [D1, ... DN, num_labels] or [D1, ... DN], where the latter implies
3093       num_labels=1. N >= 1 and num_labels is the number of target classes for
3094       the associated prediction. Commonly, N=1 and `labels` has shape
3095       [batch_size, num_labels]. [D1, ... DN] must match `predictions_idx`.
3096       Values should be in range [0, num_classes).
3097     predictions_idx: Integer `Tensor` with shape [D1, ... DN, k] where N >= 1.
3098       Commonly, N=1 and `predictions_idx` has shape [batch size, k]. The final
3099       dimension contains the top `k` predicted class indices. [D1, ... DN] must
3100       match `labels`. Values should be in range [0, num_classes).
3101     weights: `Tensor` whose rank is either 0, or n-1, where n is the rank of
3102       `labels`. If the latter, it must be broadcastable to `labels` (i.e., all
3103       dimensions must be either `1`, or the same as the corresponding `labels`
3104       dimension).
3105     metrics_collections: An optional list of collections that values should
3106       be added to.
3107     updates_collections: An optional list of collections that updates should
3108       be added to.
3109     name: Name of new update operation, and namespace for other dependent ops.
3110 
3111   Returns:
3112     mean_average_precision: Scalar `float64` `Tensor` with the mean average
3113       precision values.
3114     update: `Operation` that increments variables appropriately, and whose
3115       value matches `metric`.
3116   """
3117   with ops.name_scope(name, 'average_precision_at_top_k',
3118                       (predictions_idx, labels, weights)) as scope:
3119     # Calculate per-example average precision, and apply weights.
3120     average_precision = _sparse_average_precision_at_top_k(
3121         predictions_idx=predictions_idx, labels=labels)
3122     if weights is not None:
3123       weights = weights_broadcast_ops.broadcast_weights(
3124           math_ops.to_double(weights), average_precision)
3125       average_precision = math_ops.multiply(average_precision, weights)
3126 
3127     # Create accumulation variables and update ops for max average precision and
3128     # total average precision.
3129     with ops.name_scope(None, 'max', (average_precision,)) as max_scope:
3130       # `max` is the max possible precision. Since max for any row is 1.0:
3131       # - For the unweighted case, this is just the number of rows.
3132       # - For the weighted case, it's the sum of the weights broadcast across
3133       #   `average_precision` rows.
3134       max_var = metric_variable([], dtypes.float64, name=max_scope)
3135       if weights is None:
3136         batch_max = math_ops.to_double(
3137             array_ops.size(average_precision, name='batch_max'))
3138       else:
3139         batch_max = math_ops.reduce_sum(weights, name='batch_max')
3140       max_update = state_ops.assign_add(max_var, batch_max, name='update')
3141     with ops.name_scope(None, 'total', (average_precision,)) as total_scope:
3142       total_var = metric_variable([], dtypes.float64, name=total_scope)
3143       batch_total = math_ops.reduce_sum(average_precision, name='batch_total')
3144       total_update = state_ops.assign_add(total_var, batch_total, name='update')
3145 
3146     # Divide total by max to get mean, for both vars and the update ops.
3147     def precision_across_towers(_, total_var, max_var):
3148       return _safe_scalar_div(total_var, max_var, name='mean')
3149 
3150     mean_average_precision = _aggregate_across_towers(
3151         metrics_collections, precision_across_towers, total_var, max_var)
3152 
3153     update = _safe_scalar_div(total_update, max_update, name=scope)
3154     if updates_collections:
3155       ops.add_to_collections(updates_collections, update)
3156 
3157     return mean_average_precision, update

3206   Args:

3268       `n` label classes, where `n` is the 2nd dimension of `labels_sparse`.

3291                                                      class_id)

3293         sets.set_difference(predictions_idx, labels, aminusb=True))

3398       divided by the sum of `true_positives` and `false_positives`.

3402

3406       are not a list or tuple.

3465 @tf_export('metrics.precision_at_k')
3466 def precision_at_k(labels,
3467                    predictions,
3468                    k,
3469                    class_id=None,
3470                    weights=None,
3471                    metrics_collections=None,
3472                    updates_collections=None,
3473                    name=None):
3474   """Computes precision@k of the predictions with respect to sparse labels.
3475 
3476   If `class_id` is specified, we calculate precision by considering only the
3477       entries in the batch for which `class_id` is in the top-k highest
3478       `predictions`, and computing the fraction of them for which `class_id` is
3479       indeed a correct label.
3480   If `class_id` is not specified, we'll calculate precision as how often on
3481       average a class among the top-k classes with the highest predicted values
3482       of a batch entry is correct and can be found in the label for that entry.

3484   `precision_at_k` creates two local variables,
3485   `true_positive_at_<k>` and `false_positive_at_<k>`, that are used to compute
3486   the precision@k frequency. This frequency is ultimately returned as
3487   `precision_at_<k>`: an idempotent operation that simply divides
3488   `true_positive_at_<k>` by total (`true_positive_at_<k>` +
3489   `false_positive_at_<k>`).

3492   `update_op` operation that updates these variables and returns the
3493   `precision_at_<k>`. Internally, a `top_k` operation computes a `Tensor`
3494   indicating the top `k` `predictions`. Set operations applied to `top_k` and
3495   `labels` calculate the true positives and false positives weighted by
3496   `weights`. Then `update_op` increments `true_positive_at_<k>` and
3497   `false_positive_at_<k>` using these values.
3498 
3499   If `weights` is `None`, weights default to 1. Use weights of 0 to mask values.
3500 
3501   Args:
3502     labels: `int64` `Tensor` or `SparseTensor` with shape
3503       [D1, ... DN, num_labels] or [D1, ... DN], where the latter implies
3504       num_labels=1. N >= 1 and num_labels is the number of target classes for
3505       the associated prediction. Commonly, N=1 and `labels` has shape
3506       [batch_size, num_labels]. [D1, ... DN] must match `predictions`. Values
3507       should be in range [0, num_classes), where num_classes is the last
3508       dimension of `predictions`. Values outside this range are ignored.
3509     predictions: Float `Tensor` with shape [D1, ... DN, num_classes] where
3510       N >= 1. Commonly, N=1 and predictions has shape [batch size, num_classes].
3511       The final dimension contains the logit values for each class. [D1, ... DN]
3512       must match `labels`.
3513     k: Integer, k for @k metric.
3514     class_id: Integer class ID for which we want binary metrics. This should be
3515       in range [0, num_classes], where num_classes is the last dimension of
3516       `predictions`. If `class_id` is outside this range, the method returns
3517       NAN.
3518     weights: `Tensor` whose rank is either 0, or n-1, where n is the rank of
3519       `labels`. If the latter, it must be broadcastable to `labels` (i.e., all
3520       dimensions must be either `1`, or the same as the corresponding `labels`
3521       dimension).
3522     metrics_collections: An optional list of collections that values should
3523       be added to.
3524     updates_collections: An optional list of collections that updates should
3525       be added to.
3526     name: Name of new update operation, and namespace for other dependent ops.
3527 
3528   Returns:
3529     precision: Scalar `float64` `Tensor` with the value of `true_positives`
3530       divided by the sum of `true_positives` and `false_positives`.
3531     update_op: `Operation` that increments `true_positives` and
3532       `false_positives` variables appropriately, and whose value matches
3533       `precision`.
3534 
3535   Raises:
3536     ValueError: If `weights` is not `None` and its shape doesn't match
3537       `predictions`, or if either `metrics_collections` or `updates_collections`
3538       are not a list or tuple.
3539     RuntimeError: If eager execution is enabled.
3540   """
3541   if context.executing_eagerly():
3542     raise RuntimeError('tf.metrics.sparse_precision_at_k is not '
3543                        'supported when eager execution is enabled.')
3544 
3545   with ops.name_scope(name, _at_k_name('precision', k, class_id=class_id),
3546                       (predictions, labels, weights)) as scope:
3547     _, top_k_idx = nn.top_k(predictions, k)
3548     return precision_at_top_k(
3549         labels=labels,
3550         predictions_idx=top_k_idx,
3551         k=k,
3552         class_id=class_id,
3553         weights=weights,

3555         updates_collections=updates_collections,

3559 @tf_export('metrics.specificity_at_sensitivity')
3560 def specificity_at_sensitivity(labels,
3561                                predictions,
3562                                sensitivity,
3563                                weights=None,
3564                                num_thresholds=200,
3565                                metrics_collections=None,
3566                                updates_collections=None,
3567                                name=None):
3568   """Computes the specificity at a given sensitivity.
3569 
3570   The `specificity_at_sensitivity` function creates four local
3571   variables, `true_positives`, `true_negatives`, `false_positives` and
3572   `false_negatives` that are used to compute the specificity at the given
3573   sensitivity value. The threshold for the given sensitivity value is computed
3574   and used to evaluate the corresponding specificity.
3575 
3576   For estimation of the metric over a stream of data, the function creates an
3577   `update_op` operation that updates these variables and returns the
3578   `specificity`. `update_op` increments the `true_positives`, `true_negatives`,
3579   `false_positives` and `false_negatives` counts with the weight of each case
3580   found in the `predictions` and `labels`.
3581 
3582   If `weights` is `None`, weights default to 1. Use weights of 0 to mask values.
3583 
3584   For additional information about specificity and sensitivity, see the
3585   following: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sensitivity_and_specificity
3586 
3587   Args:
3588     labels: The ground truth values, a `Tensor` whose dimensions must match
3589       `predictions`. Will be cast to `bool`.
3590     predictions: A floating point `Tensor` of arbitrary shape and whose values
3591       are in the range `[0, 1]`.
3592     sensitivity: A scalar value in range `[0, 1]`.
3593     weights: Optional `Tensor` whose rank is either 0, or the same rank as
3594       `labels`, and must be broadcastable to `labels` (i.e., all dimensions must
3595       be either `1`, or the same as the corresponding `labels` dimension).
3596     num_thresholds: The number of thresholds to use for matching the given
3597       sensitivity.
3598     metrics_collections: An optional list of collections that `specificity`
3599       should be added to.
3600     updates_collections: An optional list of collections that `update_op` should
3601       be added to.
3602     name: An optional variable_scope name.
3603 
3604   Returns:
3605     specificity: A scalar `Tensor` representing the specificity at the given
3606       `specificity` value.
3607     update_op: An operation that increments the `true_positives`,
3608       `true_negatives`, `false_positives` and `false_negatives` variables
3609       appropriately and whose value matches `specificity`.
3610 
3611   Raises:
3612     ValueError: If `predictions` and `labels` have mismatched shapes, if
3613       `weights` is not `None` and its shape doesn't match `predictions`, or if
3614       `sensitivity` is not between 0 and 1, or if either `metrics_collections`
3615       or `updates_collections` are not a list or tuple.
3616     RuntimeError: If eager execution is enabled.
3617   """
3618   if context.executing_eagerly():
3619     raise RuntimeError('tf.metrics.specificity_at_sensitivity is not '
3620                        'supported when eager execution is enabled.')
3621 
3622   if sensitivity < 0 or sensitivity > 1:
3623     raise ValueError('`sensitivity` must be in the range [0, 1].')
3624 
3625   with variable_scope.variable_scope(name, 'specificity_at_sensitivity',
3626                                      (predictions, labels, weights)):
3627     kepsilon = 1e-7  # to account for floating point imprecisions
3628     thresholds = [
3629         (i + 1) * 1.0 / (num_thresholds - 1) for i in range(num_thresholds - 2)
3630     ]
3631     thresholds = [0.0 - kepsilon] + thresholds + [1.0 - kepsilon]
3632 
3633     values, update_ops = _confusion_matrix_at_thresholds(
3634         labels, predictions, thresholds, weights)
3635 
3636     def compute_specificity_at_sensitivity(tp, tn, fp, fn, name):
3637       """Computes the specificity at the given sensitivity.
3638 
3639       Args:
3640         tp: True positives.
3641         tn: True negatives.
3642         fp: False positives.
3643         fn: False negatives.
3644         name: The name of the operation.
3645 
3646       Returns:
3647         The specificity using the aggregated values.
3648       """
3649       sensitivities = math_ops.div(tp, tp + fn + kepsilon)
3650 
3651       # We'll need to use this trick until tf.argmax allows us to specify
3652       # whether we should use the first or last index in case of ties.
3653       min_val = math_ops.reduce_min(math_ops.abs(sensitivities - sensitivity))
3654       indices_at_minval = math_ops.equal(
3655           math_ops.abs(sensitivities - sensitivity), min_val)
3656       indices_at_minval = math_ops.to_int64(indices_at_minval)
3657       indices_at_minval = math_ops.cumsum(indices_at_minval)
3658       tf_index = math_ops.argmax(indices_at_minval, 0)
3659       tf_index = math_ops.cast(tf_index, dtypes.int32)
3660 
3661       # Now, we have the implicit threshold, so compute the specificity:
3662       return math_ops.div(tn[tf_index], tn[tf_index] + fp[tf_index] + kepsilon,
3663                           name)
3664 
3665     def specificity_across_towers(_, values):
3666       return compute_specificity_at_sensitivity(
3667           values['tp'], values['tn'], values['fp'], values['fn'], 'value')
3668 
3669     specificity = _aggregate_across_towers(
3670         metrics_collections, specificity_across_towers, values)
3671 
3672     update_op = compute_specificity_at_sensitivity(
3673         update_ops['tp'], update_ops['tn'], update_ops['fp'], update_ops['fn'],
3674         'update_op')
3675     if updates_collections:
3676       ops.add_to_collections(updates_collections, update_op)
3677 
3678     return specificity, update_op
